{"title_page": "Llangollen Canal", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox Canal\n  |name        = Llangollen Canal\n  |image       = Llangollen Canal UK.jpg\n  |image_caption     = Llangollen canal: The final narrows before Llangollen\n  |former_names      =\n  |modern_name      =\n  |original_owner     =\n  |engineer    =\n  |other_engineer  =\n  |date_act    =\n  |date_began  =\n  |date_use    =\n  |date_completed   =\n  |date_extended    =\n  |date_closed =\n  |date_restored   =\n  |len_ft         = 70\n  |len_in      = 0\n  |original_boat_length_ft       =\n  |original_boat_length_in    =\n  |len_note    =\n  |beam_ft        = 6\n  |beam_in     = 10\n  |original_beam_ft      =\n  |original_beam_in   =\n  |beam_note   = Fenders must be raised in locks \u2013 warning shown at Hurleston\n  |start_point       = [[Hurleston Junction]]\n  |original_start     =\n  |start_note  = Junction with [[Shropshire Union Canal]]\n  |end_point         = [[Llangollen]]\n  |original_end       =\n  |end_note    = Unnavigable canal continues to [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]]\n  |branch      = [[Montgomery Canal]], [[Prees Branch]], [[Ellesmere Arm]], [[Whitchurch Arm]], [[Trevor Basin]]\n  |branch_of   =\n  |connects_to        =\n  |locks       = 21\n  |original_num_locks     =\n  |lock_note   =\n  |elev_ft        = 230\n  |elev_note   =\n  |status      = Open\n  |navigation_authority         = [[Canal & River Trust]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Llangollen Canal''' ({{lang-cy|Camlas Llangollen}}) is a navigable [[canals of the United Kingdom|canal]] crossing the border between England and [[Wales]]. The waterway links [[Llangollen]] in [[Denbighshire]], north Wales, with [[Hurleston]] in south [[Cheshire]], via the town of [[Ellesmere, Shropshire]]. The name, which was coined in the 1980s, is a modern designation for parts of the historic [[Ellesmere Canal]] and the Llangollen navigable feeder, both of which became part of the [[Shropshire Union Railways and Canal Company|Shropshire Union Canals]] in 1846.\n\nThe Ellesmere Canal was proposed by industrialists at [[Ruabon]] and [[Brymbo]], and two disconnected sections were built. The northern section ran from Ellesmere Port on the [[River Mersey]] to [[Chester]], where it joined the [[Chester Canal]], and opened in 1795. Work on the southern section began at Frankton, with a line southwards to Llanymynech, and subsequently, a second section was built westwards towards Trevor. This involved crossing the [[River Ceiriog|Afon Ceiriog]] and the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]], which was achieved by building two vast aqueducts, using iron troughs to contain the water. The Ceiriog was crossed at [[Chirk]], and [[Chirk Aqueduct]] opened in 1801, to exploit local supplies of iron and coal. The canal then passed through [[Chirk Tunnel]], and reached the southern end of [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]] in 1802, which was not completed until 1805. To join the two halves up, a heavily engineered route from [[Trevor Basin]] via Ruabon and Brymbo to the River Dee at Chester was planned, but very little of it was built. Instead, the present route from Frankton to Hurleston Junction on the Chester Canal was constructed, and opened in 1805. As the route never reached the water reservoir at [[Moss Valley, Wrexham]] (built in 1786), a navigable feeder was built to Llantisilio where the [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]] weir was constructed on the River Dee to supply the canal.\n\nAs part of the Shropshire Union system, the canal from Hurleston to Llangollen thrived until the end of the First World War, after which it saw very little traffic. Navigation was formally abandoned under the terms of an Act of Abandonment obtained by the owners, the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]], in 1944, but the channel was retained as it still supplied water to the main line of the Shropshire Union, and subsequently to the Mid & South East Cheshire Water Board. This arrangement was due to end in 1954, but as there was no alternative supply of water, the powers were extended. Early pioneering cruises of the waterway were made by [[L.T.C. Rolt|Tom Rolt]] in 1947 and 1949, and despite being officially closed, a number of boats started to use it. There was a growing campaign to reopen it, but it was still designated as one of the 'waterways having insufficient commercial prospects to justify their retention for navigation' under government papers published in 1955 and 1958. It was not until the passing of the Transport Act 1968 that the route was finally designated as a cruiseway, and its future was secured. As leisure use of the canals grew, the route was rebranded as \"The Llangollen Canal\" in the 1980s, and it has become one of the most popular routes for holidaymakers. Its importance in the history of the British canal system was recognised in 2009, when the {{convert|11|mi|km|adj=on}} stretch from Gledrid Bridge near Rhoswiel to Horseshoe Falls including Pontcysyllte and Chirk aqueducts was declared a [[World Heritage site]] by [[UNESCO]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Camlas ellesmere.png|thumb|left|Map showing the planned route for the [[Ellesmere Canal]] between Chester and [[Shrewsbury]]. The feeder to Llangollen was never envisaged in the original proposal.]]\nA grand plan for the Ellesmere Canal was first proposed in 1791 by a small group of industrialists who owned coal mines, iron mines and other works near Ruabon. They wanted to link their area to the [[River Mersey]] in the north and the [[River Severn]] to the south. The northward section would link up with the [[Chester Canal]] and hence the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]] before continuing to the Mersey at Netherpool (now [[Ellesmere Port]]). The southerly section of the waterway would pass through [[Overton-on-Dee|Overton]] before heading towards [[Shrewsbury]]. There would be branches to Bersham and Brymbo, where there were ironworks, to Llanymynech, where limestone was being quarried, and it would run past [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]] to Prees. A rival group proposed a branch from the Chester Canal to reach Ruabon, via Whitchurch, with additional lines to Llanymynech and Shrewsbury. There was support for the plans of the first group, and work began, but twelve years later, the plans of the second group had largely been implemented.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=166-167}}\n\nJohn Duncombe, an engineer who was one of the original promoters, and Joseph Turner estimated that the main line to Netherpool and to Shrewsbury would cost \u00a367,456, while the whole scheme, including the branches, would cost \u00a3171,098.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=167-169}} The promoters then decided they needed an engineer with a track record to advise them, and engaged the services of [[William Jessop]], to be assisted by Duncombe and William Turner. Jessop proposed a somewhat different route south of Chester. It was the time of [[Canal Mania]], and when subscriptions were opened, 1,234 subscribers offered a total of \u00a3967,700, of which \u00a3245,500 was actually accepted. In February 1793, the two groups decided to work together, and a host of deviations and alterations were made to the plans, for which an [[Act of Parliament]] was obtained on 30 April 1793. A capital of \u00a3400,000 was authorised, with powers to raise an additional \u00a3100,000 if required, and Jessop was appointed as engineer, to be assisted by Duncombe, Thomas Denson and William Turner. On 30 October, [[Thomas Telford]] was also engaged.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=168-169}}\n\nWork began on the route southwards from Netherpool in November 1793, and packet boats started to run along it from 1 July 1795, although it was not quite finished. Three locks to connect it to the Mersey were completed in early 1796, and coal was first carried to Chester in February. The connection to the Chester Canal took a little longer, and was completed in January 1797.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=169}} The company were keen to develop the trade in limestone from Llanymynech, and cutting of the canal southwards from Frankton began in early 1794. At the time, plans for the Montgomeryshire Canal were before Parliament, which would continue southwards from Carreghofa, just beyond Llanymynech. With four locks at Frankton, and another three at Aston, the line to Carreghofa was opened in autumn 1796, and a good trade in limestone northwards, and goods southwards to the Montgomeryshire Canal, developed.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=169}}\n\nProgress north-westwards from Frankton towards [[Trevor Basin|Trevor]] was hampered by the need to cross two rivers, the Afon Ceiriog at Chirk and the Dee at Pontcysyllte. Both would require tall aqueducts, but to save construction costs at Pontcysylle, plans were drawn up for three locks at each end, to reduce the height of the main arches by {{convert|50|ft|m}}. However, on 14 July 1795 Jessop proposed that the aqueduct should be built {{convert|125|ft|m}} above the Dee, and that the costs should be saved by using an iron trough. He also proposed a similar trough at Chirk, instead of an embankment at Pont-faen, writing that \"instead of an obstruction it would be a romantic feature in the view\", and this was a major factor in persuading the landowner to allow it to be built at Chirk, rather than at Pont-faen. The foundation stone for Pontcysyllte was laid on 25 July 1795, although the committee did not formally approve the new plans until 10 August.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=170-171}}\n\nAgain, the company was keen to get trade moving on the canal, and pressed on with the line from Chirk to Frankton. The Vron Ironworks were at Chirk, with coal mines nearby, and goods from Ruabon could also be brought there by road, until the canal was completed. Work started on the Chirk aqueduct in January 1796, and when finished, it was {{convert|600|ft|m}} long with ten arches, each with a span of {{convert|40|ft|m}}, carrying the canal {{convert|70|ft|m}} above the Afon Ceiriog. It was constructed with a cast-iron bottom to the trough, but the sides were of masonry, an unusual choice given the decision to use a cast-iron trough at Pontcysyllte. The {{convert|8|mi|km|adj=on}} section from Chirk to Frankton included six locks and was completed in 1801. The section onwards through [[Chirk Tunnel|Chirk]] and Whitehouses tunnels, to reach the southern end of Pontcysyllte, opened in June 1802.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=173}}\n\nIn July 1795, the company hired contractors to start work on the branch from Hordley, near Frankton locks, to Westoncommon, which was completed in 1797. A wharf, public house, stables and other features were constructed near Westoncommon, and four lime kilns were built, to burn lime from Llanymynech using coal from Chirk. Plans for this branch to continue onwards to Shrewsbury were dropped, because lime from Weston would have to compete with that brought along the Shrewsbury Canal, and coal to supply the domestic market at Shrewsbury would not be available until Pontcysyllte aqueduct was completed. It did not appear that the route would be profitable, and this remained true when the plans were reconsidered subsequently.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=173-174}}\n\n===Joining the two halves===\n{{Llangollen Canal map}}\nPlans for joining the southern sections to the northern one were revisited by Telford in 1795, and after approval by Jessop, were authorised by Act of Parliament in 1796. They involved a heavily engineered line from Trevor to Chester, via [[Ruabon]] to the Dee at Chester, with a branch to [[Coed Talon]], which would serve the [[Brymbo]] ironworks near Ffrwd. Locks would lift the line by {{convert|76|ft|m}} from Trevor basin to Plas Kynaston, after which it would run on the level to Poolmouth and the junction with the Coed Talon Branch. It would then descend through a long flight of locks, roughly following the line of the later Chester to Wrexham railway, to enter the Dee opposite the branch to the Chester Canal. A second branch would run from Pulford to Farndon and Holt. Just over {{convert|2|mi|km}} of the Coed Talon branch was built, to a basin near Ffrwd, and although it was filled with water, it seems that it was never used, and was filled in again from 1809.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=174}}\n\nIn early 1794, a shareholder and a local landowner took out a patent for a canal lift, and offered to build a trial one. If it proved successful, then the Ellesmere company would pay for it, and if not, the inventors would meet the costs. A site was chosen on the proposed line, and by May 1796, it was ready for trials to begin. John Rennie and Jessop examined it, but like several similar ideas of the time, it was not felt to be robust enough to withstand the rigours of daily use. The company eventually paid \u00a3200 to the inventors, one quarter of the actual costs.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=174}} Jessop decided in 1800 that the route between Trevor and Chester should be abandoned, due to the changes in circumstances, and coal being available in Chester from a number of other locations.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=176}}\n\nThe Chester Canal, which had not been a financial success, had hoped that links with the Ellesmere Canal would improve their prospects, but when the Ellesmere Act of 1796 had failed to mention any connection with the Chester Canal, they had taken action, and had cut off the water supply to the northern section from Chester to Ellesmere Port. When agreement was reached on a new line from [[Frankton Junction]] to [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]], the water supply was reinstated, and work on the new line started in February 1797. The work was difficult, as it had to cross Whixall Moss, and a {{convert|261|ft|m|adj=on}} tunnel was required near [[Ellesmere, Shropshire|Ellesmere]]. It also included a branch to Prees Higher Heath, but only {{convert|3.75|mi|km|0}} of this was built, terminating at Quina Brook, where the company built some limekilns. By 1804, the main line had reached Tilstock Park, some {{convert|4|mi|km}} short of Whitchurch.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=177-178}}\n\nFurther agreement had been reached in 1802 on a route from Tilstock Park to [[Hurleston Junction]], on which work started immediately. It was completed on 25 March 1805. In order to keep the system supplied with water, an Act of Parliament obtained in 1804 had authorised the construction of a navigable feeder from the north end of Pontcysyllte aqueduct to LLangollen on onwards to Llantisilo, where the [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]] weir would be constructed on the River Dee. Once this opened in 1808, the system was not short of water. The Ellesmere company attempted to buy out the Chester Canal in 1804, but the offer had been refused. In 1813, they agreed to an amalgamation, on terms much worse than those offered in 1804, and the two companies became one from 1 July 1813.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=178-179}}\n\nThe network expanded with the opening of the Middlewich Branch on 1 September 1833,{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=181}} and the completion on the [[Birmingham and Liverpool Junction Canal]] from Nantwich Basin to Autherley on 2 March 1835.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=186}} In May 1845, the Ellesmere and Chester Canal Company obtained an Act of Parliament to enable them to absorb the Birmingham and Liverpool Junction Canal, the Montgomeryshire Canal, the [[Shrewsbury Canal]] and the [[Shropshire Canal]]. The name was changed to the [[Shropshire Union Railways and Canal Company]] in 1846, with powers to build a number of railways or convert their canals into railways,{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=232-233}} but this vision was short-lived, and they agreed to a lease with the [[London and North Western Railway]] in late 1846. An Act of Parliament was obtained to authorise this in 1847, but was not formally enacted until 1857.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=233-234}} This ended their aspirations to build railways, but they remained remarkably independent despite railway control.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=235}} The Shropshire Union was absorbed by the London and North Western Railway in late 1922, which itself became part of the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]] soon afterwards.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=249-250}}\n\n===Decline===\nAfter the takeover by the London Midland and Scottish Railway, regular maintenance was often not carried out, and gradually the canals silted up, so that boats could not operate with full loads. Traffic declined, and was significantly affected by a breach that occurred at the Perry Aqueduct, about {{convert|1|mi|km}} to the south of Frankton locks, which effectively closed the Montgomeryshire Canal to all traffic.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=65}} Traffic beyond Frankton to Llangollen had ceased in 1937, and the Frankton to Hurleston section was not used after 1939. The London Midland and Scottish Railway obtained an Act of Abandonment in 1944, allowing it to close {{convert|175|mi|km}} of canals, including much of the Shropshire Union system. However, the line from Hurleston to Llangollen and onwards to Llantisilio was saved, as it was the main supply of water to the rest of the system.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=251}}\n\nOn 6 September 1945, due to inadequate maintenance, the canal breached its banks east of [[Llangollen]] near [[Sun Bank Halt]]. The flow of hundreds of tons of water washed away the embankment of the railway further down the hill, creating a crater which was {{convert|40|yd|m}} long and {{convert|50|ft|m}} deep.{{sfn |McKnight |1987 |p=28}} This caused the first traffic of the morning, a mail and goods train composed of 16 carriages and two vans, to crash into the breach, killing one and injuring two engine crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.llangollen-railway.co.uk/hist/accid.html |work=The Llangollen Railway's History |title=1945: The Sun Bank Halt Accident |publisher=Llangollen Railway |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070101023203/http://www.llangollen-railway.co.uk/hist/accid.html |archivedate=1 January 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/denbighshire/pages/int-eist1.shtml |title=BBC News \u2013 North East Wales |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> Despite the canal being officially closed, the breach was repaired, so that water could continue to reach the main line at Hurleston. The use of the canal as a water supply channel was further bolstered by an agreement with what became the Mid & South East Cheshire Water Board,{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=251}} who used it to supply water to their Hurleston reservoir, and agreed to maintain it.\n\n== Restoration ==\nAlthough there had been little traffic since the end of the First World War, the channel had remained watered, because it supplied the main line of the Shropshire Union Canal. In the period after the Second World War, there was growing interest in using the canals for leisure cruising, and the pioneer [[L. T. C. Rolt|Tom Rolt]] attempted to cruise the canal in 1947.{{sfn |Davies |2005 |p=84}} Rolt's boat was ''Cressy'', which had been converted at Frankton to steam power, and on which Rolt had sailed westwards from Frankton Junction with Kyrle Willans after its conversion in 1930. At that time they had failed to reach Pontcysyllte.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=36}} On this occasion, he was joined by a small cruiser named ''Heron'', crewed by the Grundy family from Liverpool. The state of the canal was poor, and several of the locks were disintegrating, but despite low water levels and thick weed growth, both boats eventually reached Ellesmere. They then found that the water supply had been cut off due to a broken culvert near Chirk. After several weeks of being stranded, Rolt talked to the Chester office, and they arranged for water to be let down the canal, to enable the boats to return to Hurleston.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=37-38}} On a second attempt two years later, Rolt and his wife reached Pontcysyllte,{{sfn |Davies |2005 |p=84}} which they crossed accompanied by the actor [[Hugh Griffith]] and his wife Gunde. The Rolts moored for nearly three months just beyond the aqueduct, near the site where their boat had been built during the First World War.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=36,56}} In August they were joined by Roger Calvert and his family, who were attempting to reach the top of the canal in a home-made boat, which was pulled by a donkey. The Rolts travelled with them for part of the journey.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=58}} Edward Wilson, another canal enthusiast, reached Trevor in his boat in 1952, and the [[Inland Waterways Association]] held a rally at Llangollen later that year.{{sfn |Davies |2005 |p=84}}\n\nBy 1954, the Llangollen Canal was in a curious position. Under the terms of the LMSR Act of abandonment, obtained in 1944, navigation had been abandoned, but the right to sell water had been retained. This was to be for a period of ten years, during which those who bought the water were required to make alternative arrangements, which they failed to do. Since the nationalisation of the canals in 1948, the canal had been managed by the [[British Transport Commission]], who had to obtain Parliamentary approval to extend this arrangement. Meanwhile, a number of pleasure boats had ventured onto the canal, and there was a growing campaign to reopen the canal for navigation. A committee to spearhead this had been formed, and was chaired by the clerk for Wrexham Rural District Council, Trevor Williams. More than thirty other organisations were supporting the move, including the British Travel and Holidays Association.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=110-111}}\n\nIn 1955, the Board of Survey, a committee chaired by Lord Rusholme, had produced a report on the future of the canals under the control of the British Transport Commission, which they had divided into three categories. There were {{convert|336|mi|km}} of 'waterways to be developed', another {{convert|994|mi|km}} of 'waterways to be retained', and finally {{convert|771|mi|km}} of 'waterways having insufficient commercial prospects to justify their retention for navigation'. The Llangollen Canal was placed in the latter category, since it was still officially disused.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=116-117}} This was followed in 1958 by the Bowes Report, which suggested that the first two categories should be classified as Class A and Class B waterways, with Class B waterways put back into good working order and retained for 25 years, to attract private investment. The Llangollen Canal was still in the final category, but the report at least suggested that there should be a right of appeal against closure, and gave the first hints that such canals could be retained because of their social value for recreation.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=163}}\n\nHugh McKnight, the editor of the Inland Waterways Association's ''Bulletin'', wrote an optimistic report in 1966, pointing to the achievements of the first 20 years of the organisation's existence, mentioning the changes in public opinion concerning the canals, and pointing particularly to the growth in leisure use on the Llangollen Canal and the Oxford Canal.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=229}} Official attitudes changed, and the provisions of the Transport Act 1968 placed the canals under the control of the [[British Waterways Board]], who were tasked with maintaining, developing and running them for the benefit of users.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=233}} The whole of the branch from Hurleston Junction to Llantisilio, just below Horseshoe Falls, was listed in the Act as a cruising waterway, meaning that its future was no longer in jeopardy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1968/73/schedule/12 |title=Transport Act 1968 |publisher=The National Archives |at=Schedule 12 Part II Cruising Waterways |year=1968 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> As use by leisure craft grew, the \"Llangollen Branch of the Shropshire Union\" became popular due to its aqueducts and scenery. The canal was later renamed the Llangollen Canal, becoming one of the most popular canals for holidaymakers in Britain.{{sfn |Mosse |2010 |p=248}} The name is now used for the entire route from Hurleston to Llangollen, even though it was never described in this way during its commercial life.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=17}} It is not entirely clear when the name was first applied, since it was listed as the \"Welsh Canal\", a branch of the Shropshire Union, in 1985. At that time, potential boaters were advised that the canal was a water supply channel, and that they should submit an application containing full details and dimensions of their boat if they wanted to cruise on it. Nevertheless, they were instructed that British Waterways were keen to see leisure use of the canal, and that it could be quite congested in the summer season.{{sfn |Edwards |1985 |p=304}} Its origins as parts of two separate canals can be seen from the fact that the bridges are numbered from 1 at Hurleston to 70 at Rowsons Bridge, just past Frankton Junction. Continuing along the route to Llangollen, bridge numbering restarts at 1, while bridges 71 and upwards continue along what is now the Montgomery Canal, but was formerly the Ellesmere Branch to Llanymynech, where it joined the Montgomeryshire Canal.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=29,67}}\n\nA notable feature of the canal is the [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]], built by [[Thomas Telford]]. Opened in 1805, the aqueduct is more than {{convert|300|m}} long and {{convert|38|m}} above the valley floor. It has 19 stone arches, each with a 45-foot (14 metre) span. Another aqueduct carries the canal over the [[Ceiriog Valley|River Ceiriog]] at [[Chirk]], and there are tunnels nearby at Whitehouses, Chirk, and Ellesmere.\n\nThe canal also forms the boundary on two sides of the [[Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses NNR|Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses National Nature Reserve]]. In 2009 an eleven-mile section of the canal from Gledrid Bridge near Rhoswiel through to the [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]], which includes [[Chirk Aqueduct]] and [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]], was declared a [[World Heritage site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/visual_arts/architecture_and_design/article6594604.ece |title=Unesco names Pontcysyllte aqueduct as UK's latest World Heritage site |date=28 June 2009 |accessdate=12 January 2010 |newspaper=The Times |location=London}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Llangollen canal wharf.jpg|Llangollen canal wharf.\nFile:pontcysyllte aqueduct arp.jpg|A [[narrowboat]] traverses the [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]].\n</gallery>\n\n== Route ==\n=== Hurleston to Frankton Junction ===\n{{Ellesmere Canal Hurleston Branch map|Hurleston to Frankton Junction}}\n\nThe canal at Hurleston Junction rises from the Shropshire Union Canal main line, through four adjacent locks, with a total rise of {{convert|34|ft|3|in|m}}.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=18}} The canal had been an early pioneer in the use of iron lock gates, instead of the more traditional wooden ones, and this material was first used on the locks at Frankton in 1819.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=179}} The four locks here have a mixture of wooden and metal gates. All were built by the engineer J Fletcher around 1805. Lock 1 has metal lower gates, and a wooden upper gate, while gates at both ends of lock 2 are made of metal. The metal gates on both locks were replaced in 1974.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138544 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 1 (east)}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num=1136468 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 2}}</ref> Locks 3 and 4 have a single metal gate at the upper end, and wooden mitre gates at the lower end. Like many of the structures on the canal, they are [[grade II listed]] structures.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1330142 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 3}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num=1136476 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 4 (west)}}</ref>\n\nBeside the locks is Hurleston Reservoir, which has a capacity of {{convert|85|e6impgal|Ml}}. It is supplied with water that flows down the canal from Horseshoe Falls at Llantisilio, and is used both for drinking water and to supply the main line of the Shropshire Union Canal.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=19}}\nWater enters it through a side channel with sluices and a weir, just above lock number 4. The treatment works on the west bank is now operated by United Utilities, and was given a \u00a36 million upgrade in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mgf.ltd.uk/case-study/case-study-water-treatment-works-at-hurleston/ |title=Case Study - Hurleston Water Treatment Works |publisher=MGF |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nJust beyond the A534 Wrexham Road bridge is the entrance to Swanley Bridge Marina, on the west bank of the canal. It has moorings for over 300 boats, and is situated in {{convert|250|acre|ha}} of farmland, which includes a {{convert|7|acre|ha|adj=on}} wood with nature trails. It opened in September 2006, and was built in response to a document published by British Waterways in the spring of that year, which outlined development opportunities for farmers and landowners adjacent to the canal.<ref>{{cite book |title=Llangollen Canal Marina |publisher=Waterways World |date=November 2006 |issn=0309-1422}}</ref>\n\nThe two Swanley locks raise the level of the canal by another {{convert|12|ft|10|in|m}},{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=18}} and by the upper lock is the grade II listed Swanley Hall, a red-brick farmhouse parts of which date from the early 16th century.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138575 |desc=Swanley Hall |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> Baddiley Hall, which has three storeys and an attic, and dates from the late 17th century, is set some distance back from the canal.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138585 |desc=Baddiley Hall |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> In its grounds is the [[grade I listed]] parish church of St. Michael, the chancel of which dates from 1308, while the nave dates from 1811.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138586 |desc=Church of St. Michael |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> Both are separated from the canal by a [[scheduled monument]] site, containing the earthworks and buried remains of an abandoned medieval village.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1018822 |desc=Medieval village remains east of Baddiley Hall |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> The three Baddiley locks follow, with a combined rise of {{convert|19|ft|8|in|m}}.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=18}}\n \n[[File:Bridge \"Wrenbury Lift ^2\" - geograph.org.uk - 336435.jpg|thumb|left|Wrenbury Church lift bridge is one of three in the village.]]\nAfter passing Wrenbury Hall, on the west bank, the canal turns to the west, and is crossed by the Wrenbury Church lift bridge, the first of three lift-bridges in the village.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=20-21}} It is formed of timber planks fixed between wooden beams, and the bridge deck is hinged at the northern end. A weighted counterbalance allows the bridge to be opened, and the structure is [[grade II* listed]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1357482 |desc=Wrenbury Church lift bridge |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> [[Wrenbury]] lift bridge, No. 20, is automated, with push-button controls. It is operated by use of a British Waterways key, and involves closing barriers and stopping traffic on a sometimes-busy road. Wrenbury Wharf is next to the bridge, where the former mill building has been reused by a boatyard, and a nearby warehouse has become a pub.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=20}}\n\nAt [[Grindley Brook]], the canal was crossed by the defunct [[Whitchurch and Tattenhall Railway]]. The railway and the nearby [[Grindley Brook Halt railway station]] closed in 1957,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shropshirehistory.com/railways/stations.htm|title=Stations|work=Shropshire History|accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> and goods traffic ceased in 1963, but the massive embankments and bridge remain. Immediately afterwards, the canal passes through three locks and a three-chamber staircase lock, attended during summer months by a [[lock keeper]]. The six locks raise the level of the canal by {{convert|38|ft|11|in|m}}. After another mile (1.6&nbsp;km), there is a lift bridge just before the entrance to the Whitchurch Arm, which served the town of [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]]. Part of it remains open, and is used for moorings.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=22-23}} The section from the main line to Sherryman's Bridge was opened on 6 July 1808, and in 1811 a further extension into the town reached Castle Well.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=178}} The arm remained closed when the canal reopened in the 1950s, but Whitchurch Town Council looked at ways of bringing boats back into the town in the early 1980s{{sfn |Squires |2008 |p=113}} and the embryonic [[Whitchurch Waterway Trust]] was formed in 1986, with the aim of reopening the arm, of which around {{convert|0.75|mi|km}} was left, the rest having been built over in the 1950s.{{sfn |Squires |2008 |p=113}} This was achieved in October 1993, and the trust are hopeful that a new route into the town can be constructed.{{sfn |Squires |2008 |pp=118, 134}}\n\nBetween bridges 42 and 47, the canal skirts the eastern edge and then passes through and the southern edge of Whixall Moss, part of the [[Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses National Nature Reserve]]. With a combined area of nearly {{convert|2500|acre|km2}}, they form the third largest area of raised peat bog in the United Kingdom. The reserve is also a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]], a European [[Special Area of Conservation]] and a Wetland of International Importance under the [[Ramsar site|Ramsar Convention]]. The bogs were drained using powers enshrined in Enclosure Acts dating from 1777 and 1823, and further drainage took place when the canal was built in 1804, and again in 1863 when a railway was built along the north-western margins. Commercial peat cutting using mechanised cutters began in 1968, but extraction ceased in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/sites/www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/files/NNR_Fenns_Whixall_leaflet.pdf |title=Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses National Nature Reserve |publisher=Natural England |pp=4\u20135 |accessdate=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313214315/http://www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/sites/www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/files/NNR_Fenns_Whixall_leaflet.pdf |archive-date=13 March 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe technical difficulties of cutting a canal through Whixall Moss were many, but Jessop and Telford decided on a direct route across the moss, rather than building a bypass that skirted round the edge of the area. The water table in the Moss was lowered by drainage and a raft was constructed, on which the canal was built.<ref name=sucs>{{cite web |url=http://www.shropshireunion.org.uk/the-canals/early-history |title=Early History of the Shropshire Union Canals |publisher=Shropshire Union Canal Society |accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> The canal had to float across the peat, and the engineers understood that regular maintenance of this section would be a requirement for many years. They employed a team of navvies to build up the banks with more clay on a continuous basis, who became known as the Whixall Moss Gang.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/england/shropshire/article_2.shtml |title=The Whixall Moss Gang (2) |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales / BBC |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> Clay was obtained from the clay pit which became Whixall Marina, and was transferred to the work site in horse-drawn barges. Men were employed on this work from 1804 until 1960, working five and a half days a week, and became the longest serving group of navvies ever to work on the British canals. In the 1960s, the engineering issues that created the work were solved, and they were all laid off.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/england/shropshire/article_3.shtml |title=The Whixall Moss Gang (3) |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales / BBC |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> The solution adopted to prevent the canal sinking further into the peat was to underpin the whole section with steel piling.<ref name=sucs/>\n\nAdjacent to bridge 46 is Whixall Moss Junction leading to the Prees Branch.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=25}} Two breaches of the canal have occurred near Whixall in recent years. The first was in 2004 at Hampton Bank, near bridge 50, when badgers burrowed into the bank, causing it to fail. The animals were also implicated in a breach some {{convert|440|yd|m}} to the east of Cornhill Bridge 47, which occurred in late 2009. The bank failed as new piling was being driven in, but had previously been weakened by burrowing.{{sfn |Minifie |2010 |p=46}}\n\nAs the canal approaches Ellesmere, it passes a series of [[Mere (lake)|meres]]. Cole Mere is very close to the south bank of the canal, but at a lower level. Blake Mere is on the towpath side, with only the towpath separating it from the canal in places. Both are surrounded by woods, and the canal is fringed by oak trees, many planted by the Shropshire Union Company to ensure that they had supplies of timber to replace their fleet of wooden boats as that became necessary. At the far end of Blake Mere is the short Ellesmere Tunnel, just {{convert|87|yd|m}} long, and beyond that the market town of [[Ellesmere, Shropshire|Ellesmere]]. A short branch leads into the town,{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=26-27}} at the end of which is a three-storey, red brick warehouse, dating from the early 19th century, which is grade II listed.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1055499 |desc=Canal Warehouse |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> At the junction is a Canal and River Trust maintenance depot, housed in a series of buildings which are all grade II* listed. The complex includes Beech House, the offices of the Ellesmere Canal Company from 1806, but now converted into flats. The range of buildings form the best-preserved canal maintenance yard in Britain.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1176445 |desc=Beech House Canal Maintenance Depot |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> The former stables and stores, which are now used as offices, include an exceptionally early example of a covered dry dock, in which barges were built and repaired. It predates the better known examples of covered slips at the naval dockyards of [[HMNB Devonport|Devonport]] and [[Chatham Dockyard|Chatham]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1366122 |desc=Canal Maintenance Depot South East Side |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe canal also passes through [[Burland]], [[Quoisley Bridge]], and [[Bettisfield]].\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Prees Branch=== <!-- This is linked to by a redirect \"Prees Branch\" -->\n{{Prees Branch Canal Route Map}}\nThe Prees Arm of the canal was originally intended to reach [[Prees]], but only the first {{convert|3.75|mi|km}} were constructed, terminating at [[Quina Brook]]. Much of the ground through which it passed is formed of peat.{{sfn |Edwards |1985 |p=305}} Today it is only open for 7 [[furlong]]s (1.4&nbsp;km), with two lift bridges, to a [[marina]] at the end of the navigable part; beyond that, another {{convert|0.62|mi|km|0}}, as far as Waterloo Bridge,{{sfn |Edwards |1985 |p=310}} is partially watered and forms the [[Prees Branch Canal Nature Reserve]]. The remaining {{convert|2|mi|km}} is dry, but can be followed in the landscape as most of it is marked by trees growing along its course.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/@52.8872502,-2.7265292,1163m/data=!3m1!1e3 |title=Satellite view |publisher=Google maps}}</ref> The towpath is on the eastern bank from the junction to Dobson's Bridge, and then crosses over to the other side, where it remained to the end of the canal at Quina Brook.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=25}}\n\nNext to the junction is a toll-keeper's cottage dating from around 1800, the time of the construction of the canal. It has since been reused as a farmhouse.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237205 |desc=Roving Bridge House |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> Allman's Bridge dates from the construction of the canal, although there have been some later repairs to the structure. The wooden decking is opened by a counterweight and chains.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237206 |desc=Allman's Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> It was one of the last manual lift bridges to be converted to hydraulic operation in 2010. Nearby is a single arched [[squinch]] bridge, again dating from the early 1800s and constructed in red bricks. It crosses a drainage ditch, probably associated with the drainage of Whixall Moss, which passes under the canal at this point.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237334 |desc=Squinch bridge over stream north east of Allmans Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> Starks Bridge is another wooden lift bridge, and as well as being grade II* listed, is a scheduled ancient monument.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1244333 |desc=Starks Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> It is a rare example of a skewed lift bridge.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p-24}} Dobson's Bridge, a fixed [[humpback bridge]] made of red bricks with an elliptical arch, was classified in 1987 as a Grade Il [[listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237207 |desc=Dobson's Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the navigable section is Whixall Marina, which was constructed on the site of some clay pits, which for many years supplied clay used for puddling of the canals.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=24}} From 2017 to 2018, the marina had been refurbished with the addition of a waterside cafe, car park and new shower and toilet facilities. It is also near the famous Whixall Moss which is used by many walkers. On the nature reserve section, Boodles Bridge is of similar construction and date to Dobson's Bridge.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237348 |desc=Boodles Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> At the far end of the canal are the remains of two groups of limekilns, the main group consisting of four kilns built of red brick and sandstone rubble. They were built at the same time as the branch was constructed.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1236700 |desc=Limekilns |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Prees-branch.png|Old map showing the complete branch to Quina Brook\nFile:WhixallMarinaEvening.jpg|Evening over Whixall Marina\n</gallery>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Frankton Junction to Trevor Basin ===\n{{Ellesmere Canal Main Line map|Frankton Junction to Trevor Basin}}\nAt Frankton Junction the [[Montgomery Canal]], which is partially restored, heads southwards. For historic reasons the bridge numbering continues down the Montgomery Canal and a second bridge numbering series for the Llangollen Canal begins with Rowson's Bridge (which is numbered both 1W and 70). The \"W\" addition was part of a Minimum Safety Standards scheme instigated by British Waterways, to avoid possible confusion, especially for emergency services, of having different bridges on the same canal with the same number. British Waterways consulted with the Inland Waterways Association and the Shropshire Union Canal Society before finally deciding to add the \"W\", and at the same time as the numbers were altered, it ensured that all bridges carried a number on both sides. The work was due to be completed by July 2008, but there were delays due to manufacturing difficulties with the new castings.{{sfn |Minifie |2008 |p=56}}\n\nThe Llangollen Canal passes through [[Hindford]], [[St Martin's, Shropshire|Saint Martin's]], [[Preesgweene]], [[Chirk Bank]], [[Chirk]] and [[Froncysyllte]], and includes the [[Chirk Aqueduct]], the [[Chirk Tunnel]] and the [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]].\n\n<gallery perrow=\"3\">\nFile:FranktonJunction-01s.jpg|[[Frankton Junction]]\nFile:NewMartonBottomLock 01s.jpg|New Marton Bottom Lock\nFile:NewMartonTopLock 01s.jpg|New Marton Top Lock\nFile:Y Waun AqueductWales.JPG|[[Chirk Aqueduct]]\nFile:Chirk tunnel.jpg|[[Chirk Tunnel]]\nFile:TrevorBasin-01s.jpg|[[Trevor Basin]]\n</gallery>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Trevor Basin to Horseshoe Falls ===\n{{Ellesmere Canal Llangollen Branch map|Trevor Basin to Horseshoe Falls}}\nThis section was built as a navigable feeder and is both shallow and narrow. Some sections near Llangollen are too narrow for boats to pass each other and it is necessary to scout ahead to check for oncoming boats. Navigation should not be attempted by boats with a draught of more than {{convert|21|in|cm}}.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=30}} A number of breaches had occurred on this final section over many years, and in the early 1980s, British Waterways initiated a programme to resolve this issue. Parts of it were rebuilt with a concrete lining, which included a waterproof membrane to retain the water, and a system of drainage pipes underneath the bed, to prevent water building up and damaging the construction.{{sfn |Goss |2009 |p=84}}\n\nNavigation by powered craft is prohibited beyond the entrance to Llangollen Marina and the final section is used only by horse drawn trip boats. The current boats maintain a long tradition, which was first offered to visitors in 1884.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=33}} The towpath beside the feeder is in good condition, and walkers can reach the weir at Horseshoe Falls.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=33-34}} [[British Waterways]] maintains a gravel [[shoal]] immediately upstream of the marina entrance past Llangollen Wharf. This maintains a draught which most [[narrowboat]]s cannot pass, but which is passable by the shallow draughted trip boats.\n\nIn 2005, a marina was constructed by British Waterways, just upstream from Llangollen Wharf, to relieve the acute shortage of casual moorings, and provides 33 berths. About {{convert|100|yd|m}} downstream of the wharf there are about a dozen visitor moorings complete with individual electricity and water pedestals at each. Similar pedestals have also been installed at the marina berths. Mooring in Llangollen is restricted to 48 hours, and a charge is made both at the marina and the visitor moorings, which are below bridge 45.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=34}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Transport|Cheshire}}\n*[[Canals of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[History of the British canal system]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Bolton |first=David\n  |title=Race Against Time\n  |date=1990\n  |publisher=Methuen\n  |isbn=978-0-413-63470-2\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Davies |first=Robert\n  |title=Llangollen and Pontcysyllte\n  |date=August 2005\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Denton |first=John Horsley\n  |title=Montgomershire Canal and the Llanymynech Branch of the Ellesmere Canal\n  |year=1984\n  |publisher=Lapal Publications\n  |isbn=978-0-9509238-1-9\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book \n  |first=L A |last=Edwards\n  |title=Inland Waterways of Great Britain (6th Ed)\n  |publisher=Imray Laurie Norie and Wilson\n  |year=1985\n  |isbn=978-0-85288-081-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Goss |first=Keith\n  |title=WW Guide to the Llangollen Canal\n  |date=July 2009\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book \n  |first=Charles |last=Hadfield \n  |title=The Canals of the West Midlands \n  |publisher=David and Charles \n  |year=1985 \n  |isbn=978-0-7153-8644-6\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |first=Hugh |last=McKnight\n  |title=The Shell Book of Inland Waterways\n  |publisher=[[David & Charles]]\n  |year=1987\n  |isbn=978-0-7153-8239-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Minifie |first=Michael\n  |title=Renumbered Bridges\n  |date=December 2008\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Minifie |first=Michael\n  |title=Llangollen Canal\n  |date=January 2010\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |first=Jonathan |last=Mosse\n  |title=Waterways of Britain\n  |publisher=Times Books\n  |year=2010\n  |isbn=978-0-00-787363-0\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |last=Nicholson\n  |authorlink=Nicholson Guides\n  |title=Nicholson Guides Vol 4: Four Counties and the Welsh Canals\n  |publisher=Harper Collins\n  |year=2006\n  |isbn=978-0-00-721112-8\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Waterways World\n  |title=Canal Guide 2 \u2013 Llangollen and Montgomery Canals\n  |year=2005\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |isbn=978-1-870002-89-9\n  |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610093308/http://www.northwalesborderlands.co.uk/explore-north-wales-borderlands/heritage.aspx Llangollen Canal] \u2013 North Wales Borderlands website\n\n{{Canals of Britain}}\n\n{{Coord|52.9722|N|3.1711|W|display=title|region:GB_type:river}}\n\n[[Category:Llangollen Canal| ]]\n[[Category:Canals in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Canals in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Canals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Shropshire Union Canal]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Denbighshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox Canal\n  |name        = Llangollen Canal\n  |image       = Llangollen Canal UK.jpg\n  |image_caption     = Llangollen canal: The final narrows before Llangollen\n  |former_names      =\n  |modern_name      =\n  |original_owner     =\n  |engineer    =\n  |other_engineer  =\n  |date_act    =\n  |date_began  =\n  |date_use    =\n  |date_completed   =\n  |date_extended    =\n  |date_closed =\n  |date_restored   =\n  |len_ft         = 70\n  |len_in      = 0\n  |original_boat_length_ft       =\n  |original_boat_length_in    =\n  |len_note    =\n  |beam_ft        = 6\n  |beam_in     = 10\n  |original_beam_ft      =\n  |original_beam_in   =\n  |beam_note   = Fenders must be raised in locks \u2013 warning shown at Hurleston\n  |start_point       = [[Hurleston Junction]]\n  |original_start     =\n  |start_note  = Junction with [[Shropshire Union Canal]]\n  |end_point         = [[Llangollen]]\n  |original_end       =\n  |end_note    = Unnavigable canal continues to [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]]\n  |branch      = [[Montgomery Canal]], [[Prees Branch]], [[Ellesmere Arm]], [[Whitchurch Arm]], [[Trevor Basin]]\n  |branch_of   =\n  |connects_to        =\n  |locks       = 21\n  |original_num_locks     =\n  |lock_note   =\n  |elev_ft        = 230\n  |elev_note   =\n  |status      = Open\n  |navigation_authority         = [[Canal & River Trust]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Llangollen Canal''' ({{lang-cy|Camlas Llangollen}}) is a navigable [[canals of the United Kingdom|canal]] crossing the border between England and [[Wales]]. The waterway links [[Llangollen]] in [[Denbighshire]], north Wales, with [[Hurleston]] in south [[Cheshire]], via the town of [[Ellesmere, Shropshire]]. The name, which was coined in the 1980s, is a modern designation for parts of the historic [[Ellesmere Canal]] and the Llangollen navigable feeder, both of which became part of the [[Shropshire Union Railways and Canal Company|Shropshire Union Canals]] in 1846.\n\nThe Ellesmere Canal was proposed by industrialists at [[Ruabon]] and [[Brymbo]], and two disconnected sections were built. The northern section ran from Ellesmere Port on the [[River Mersey]] to [[Chester]], where it joined the [[Chester Canal]], and opened in 1795. Work on the southern section began at Frankton, with a line southwards to Llanymynech, and subsequently, a second section was built westwards towards Trevor. This involved crossing the [[River Ceiriog|Afon Ceiriog]] and the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]], which was achieved by building two vast aqueducts, using iron troughs to contain the water. The Ceiriog was crossed at [[Chirk]], and [[Chirk Aqueduct]] opened in 1801, to exploit local supplies of iron and coal. The canal then passed through [[Chirk Tunnel]], and reached the southern end of [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]] in 1802, which was not completed until 1805. To join the two halves up, a heavily engineered route from [[Trevor Basin]] via Ruabon and Brymbo to the River Dee at Chester was planned, but very little of it was built. Instead, the present route from Frankton to Hurleston Junction on the Chester Canal was constructed, and opened in 1805. As the route never reached the water reservoir at [[Moss Valley, Wrexham]] (built in 1786), a navigable feeder was built to Llantisilio where the [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]] weir was constructed on the River Dee to supply the canal.\n\nAs part of the Shropshire Union system, the canal from Hurleston to Llangollen thrived until the end of the First World War, after which it saw very little traffic. Navigation was formally abandoned under the terms of an Act of Abandonment obtained by the owners, the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]], in 1944, but the channel was retained as it still supplied water to the main line of the Shropshire Union, and subsequently to the Mid & South East Cheshire Water Board. This arrangement was due to end in 1954, but as there was no alternative supply of water, the powers were extended. Early pioneering cruises of the waterway were made by [[L.T.C. Rolt|Tom Rolt]] in 1947 and 1949, and despite being officially closed, a number of boats started to use it. There was a growing campaign to reopen it, but it was still designated as one of the 'waterways having insufficient commercial prospects to justify their retention for navigation' under government papers published in 1955 and 1958. It was not until the passing of the Transport Act 1968 that the route was finally designated as a cruiseway, and its future was secured. As leisure use of the canals grew, the route was rebranded as \"The Llangollen Canal\" in the 1980s, and it has become one of the most popular routes for holidaymakers. Its importance in the history of the British canal system was recognised in 2009, when the {{convert|11|mi|km|adj=on}} stretch from Gledrid Bridge near Rhoswiel to Horseshoe Falls including Pontcysyllte and Chirk aqueducts was declared a [[World Heritage site]] by [[UNESCO]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Camlas ellesmere.png|thumb|left|Map showing the planned route for the [[Ellesmere Canal]] between Chester and [[Shrewsbury]]. The feeder to Llangollen was never envisaged in the original proposal.]]\nA grand plan for the Ellesmere Canal was first proposed in 1791 by a small group of industrialists who owned coal mines, iron mines and other works near Ruabon. They wanted to link their area to the [[River Mersey]] in the north and the [[River Severn]] to the south. The northward section would link up with the [[Chester Canal]] and hence the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]] before continuing to the Mersey at Netherpool (now [[Ellesmere Port]]). The southerly section of the waterway would pass through [[Overton-on-Dee|Overton]] before heading towards [[Shrewsbury]]. There would be branches to Bersham and Brymbo, where there were ironworks, to Llanymynech, where limestone was being quarried, and it would run past [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]] to Prees. A rival group proposed a branch from the Chester Canal to reach Ruabon, via Whitchurch, with additional lines to Llanymynech and Shrewsbury. There was support for the plans of the first group, and work began, but twelve years later, the plans of the second group had largely been implemented.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=166-167}}\n\nJohn Duncombe, an engineer who was one of the original promoters, and Joseph Turner estimated that the main line to Netherpool and to Shrewsbury would cost \u00a367,456, while the whole scheme, including the branches, would cost \u00a3171,098.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=167-169}} The promoters then decided they needed an engineer with a track record to advise them, and engaged the services of [[William Jessop]], to be assisted by Duncombe and William Turner. Jessop proposed a somewhat different route south of Chester. It was the time of [[Canal Mania]], and when subscriptions were opened, 1,234 subscribers offered a total of \u00a3967,700, of which \u00a3245,500 was actually accepted. In February 1793, the two groups decided to work together, and a host of deviations and alterations were made to the plans, for which an [[Act of Parliament]] was obtained on 30 April 1793. A capital of \u00a3400,000 was authorised, with powers to raise an additional \u00a3100,000 if required, and Jessop was appointed as engineer, to be assisted by Duncombe, Thomas Denson and William Turner. On 30 October, [[Thomas Telford]] was also engaged.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=168-169}}\n\nWork began on the route southwards from Netherpool in November 1793, and packet boats started to run along it from 1 July 1795, although it was not quite finished. Three locks to connect it to the Mersey were completed in early 1796, and coal was first carried to Chester in February. The connection to the Chester Canal took a little longer, and was completed in January 1797.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=169}} The company were keen to develop the trade in limestone from Llanymynech, and cutting of the canal southwards from Frankton began in early 1794. At the time, plans for the Montgomeryshire Canal were before Parliament, which would continue southwards from Carreghofa, just beyond Llanymynech. With four locks at Frankton, and another three at Aston, the line to Carreghofa was opened in autumn 1796, and a good trade in limestone northwards, and goods southwards to the Montgomeryshire Canal, developed.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=169}}\n\nProgress north-westwards from Frankton towards [[Trevor Basin|Trevor]] was hampered by the need to cross two rivers, the Afon Ceiriog at Chirk and the Dee at Pontcysyllte. Both would require tall aqueducts, but to save construction costs at Pontcysylle, plans were drawn up for three locks at each end, to reduce the height of the main arches by {{convert|50|ft|m}}. However, on 14 July 1795 Jessop proposed that the aqueduct should be built {{convert|125|ft|m}} above the Dee, and that the costs should be saved by using an iron trough. He also proposed a similar trough at Chirk, instead of an embankment at Pont-faen, writing that \"instead of an obstruction it would be a romantic feature in the view\", and this was a major factor in persuading the landowner to allow it to be built at Chirk, rather than at Pont-faen. The foundation stone for Pontcysyllte was laid on 25 July 1795, although the committee did not formally approve the new plans until 10 August.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=170-171}}\n\nAgain, the company was keen to get trade moving on the canal, and pressed on with the line from Chirk to Frankton. The Vron Ironworks were at Chirk, with coal mines nearby, and goods from Ruabon could also be brought there by road, until the canal was completed. Work started on the Chirk aqueduct in January 1796, and when finished, it was {{convert|600|ft|m}} long with ten arches, each with a span of {{convert|40|ft|m}}, carrying the canal {{convert|70|ft|m}} above the Afon Ceiriog. It was constructed with a cast-iron bottom to the trough, but the sides were of masonry, an unusual choice given the decision to use a cast-iron trough at Pontcysyllte. The {{convert|8|mi|km|adj=on}} section from Chirk to Frankton included six locks and was completed in 1801. The section onwards through [[Chirk Tunnel|Chirk]] and Whitehouses tunnels, to reach the southern end of Pontcysyllte, opened in June 1802.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=173}}\n\nIn July 1795, the company hired contractors to start work on the branch from Hordley, near Frankton locks, to Westoncommon, which was completed in 1797. A wharf, public house, stables and other features were constructed near Westoncommon, and four lime kilns were built, to burn lime from Llanymynech using coal from Chirk. Plans for this branch to continue onwards to Shrewsbury were dropped, because lime from Weston would have to compete with that brought along the Shrewsbury Canal, and coal to supply the domestic market at Shrewsbury would not be available until Pontcysyllte aqueduct was completed. It did not appear that the route would be profitable, and this remained true when the plans were reconsidered subsequently.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=173-174}}\n\n===Joining the two halves===\n{{Llangollen Canal map}}\nPlans for joining the southern sections to the northern one were revisited by Telford in 1795, and after approval by Jessop, were authorised by Act of Parliament in 1796. They involved a heavily engineered line from Trevor to Chester, via [[Ruabon]] to the Dee at Chester, with a branch to [[Coed Talon]], which would serve the [[Brymbo]] ironworks near Ffrwd. Locks would lift the line by {{convert|76|ft|m}} from Trevor basin to Plas Kynaston, after which it would run on the level to Poolmouth and the junction with the Coed Talon Branch. It would then descend through a long flight of locks, roughly following the line of the later Chester to Wrexham railway, to enter the Dee opposite the branch to the Chester Canal. A second branch would run from Pulford to Farndon and Holt. Just over {{convert|2|mi|km}} of the Coed Talon branch was built, to a basin near Ffrwd, and although it was filled with water, it seems that it was never used, and was filled in again from 1809.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=174}}\n\nIn early 1794, a shareholder and a local landowner took out a patent for a canal lift, and offered to build a trial one. If it proved successful, then the Ellesmere company would pay for it, and if not, the inventors would meet the costs. A site was chosen on the proposed line, and by May 1796, it was ready for trials to begin. John Rennie and Jessop examined it, but like several similar ideas of the time, it was not felt to be robust enough to withstand the rigours of daily use. The company eventually paid \u00a3200 to the inventors, one quarter of the actual costs.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=174}} Jessop decided in 1800 that the route between Trevor and Chester should be abandoned, due to the changes in circumstances, and coal being available in Chester from a number of other locations.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=176}}\n\nThe Chester Canal, which had not been a financial success, had hoped that links with the Ellesmere Canal would improve their prospects, but when the Ellesmere Act of 1796 had failed to mention any connection with the Chester Canal, they had taken action, and had cut off the water supply to the northern section from Chester to Ellesmere Port. When agreement was reached on a new line from [[Frankton Junction]] to [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]], the water supply was reinstated, and work on the new line started in February 1797. The work was difficult, as it had to cross Whixall Moss, and a {{convert|261|ft|m|adj=on}} tunnel was required near [[Ellesmere, Shropshire|Ellesmere]]. It also included a branch to Prees Higher Heath, but only {{convert|3.75|mi|km|0}} of this was built, terminating at Quina Brook, where the company built some limekilns. By 1804, the main line had reached Tilstock Park, some {{convert|4|mi|km}} short of Whitchurch.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=177-178}}\n\nFurther agreement had been reached in 1802 on a route from Tilstock Park to [[Hurleston Junction]], on which work started immediately. It was completed on 25 March 1805. In order to keep the system supplied with water, an Act of Parliament obtained in 1804 had authorised the construction of a navigable feeder from the north end of Pontcysyllte aqueduct to LLangollen on onwards to Llantisilo, where the [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]] weir would be constructed on the River Dee. Once this opened in 1808, the system was not short of water. The Ellesmere company attempted to buy out the Chester Canal in 1804, but the offer had been refused. In 1813, they agreed to an amalgamation, on terms much worse than those offered in 1804, and the two companies became one from 1 July 1813.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=178-179}}\n\nThe network expanded with the opening of the Middlewich Branch on 1 September 1833,{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=181}} and the completion on the [[Birmingham and Liverpool Junction Canal]] from Nantwich Basin to Autherley on 2 March 1835.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=186}} In May 1845, the Ellesmere and Chester Canal Company obtained an Act of Parliament to enable them to absorb the Birmingham and Liverpool Junction Canal, the Montgomeryshire Canal, the [[Shrewsbury Canal]] and the [[Shropshire Canal]]. The name was changed to the [[Shropshire Union Railways and Canal Company]] in 1846, with powers to build a number of railways or convert their canals into railways,{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=232-233}} but this vision was short-lived, and they agreed to a lease with the [[London and North Western Railway]] in late 1846. An Act of Parliament was obtained to authorise this in 1847, but was not formally enacted until 1857.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=233-234}} This ended their aspirations to build railways, but they remained remarkably independent despite railway control.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=235}} The Shropshire Union was absorbed by the London and North Western Railway in late 1922, which itself became part of the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]] soon afterwards.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |pp=249-250}}\n\n===Decline===\nAfter the takeover by the London Midland and Scottish Railway, regular maintenance was often not carried out, and gradually the canals silted up, so that boats could not operate with full loads. Traffic declined, and was significantly affected by a breach that occurred at the Perry Aqueduct, about {{convert|1|mi|km}} to the south of Frankton locks, which effectively closed the Montgomeryshire Canal to all traffic.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=65}} Traffic beyond Frankton to Llangollen had ceased in 1937, and the Frankton to Hurleston section was not used after 1939. The London Midland and Scottish Railway obtained an Act of Abandonment in 1944, allowing it to close {{convert|175|mi|km}} of canals, including much of the Shropshire Union system. However, the line from Hurleston to Llangollen and onwards to Llantisilio was saved, as it was the main supply of water to the rest of the system.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=251}}\n\nOn 6 September 1945, due to inadequate maintenance, the canal breached its banks east of [[Llangollen]] near [[Sun Bank Halt]]. The flow of hundreds of tons of water washed away the embankment of the railway further down the hill, creating a crater which was {{convert|40|yd|m}} long and {{convert|50|ft|m}} deep.{{sfn |McKnight |1987 |p=28}} This caused the first traffic of the morning, a mail and goods train composed of 16 carriages and two vans, to crash into the breach, killing one and injuring two engine crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.llangollen-railway.co.uk/hist/accid.html |work=The Llangollen Railway's History |title=1945: The Sun Bank Halt Accident |publisher=Llangollen Railway |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070101023203/http://www.llangollen-railway.co.uk/hist/accid.html |archivedate=1 January 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/denbighshire/pages/int-eist1.shtml |title=BBC News \u2013 North East Wales |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> Despite the canal being officially closed, the breach was repaired, so that water could continue to reach the main line at Hurleston. The use of the canal as a water supply channel was further bolstered by an agreement with what became the Mid & South East Cheshire Water Board,{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=251}} who used it to supply water to their Hurleston reservoir, and agreed to maintain it.\n\n== Restoration ==\nAlthough there had been little traffic since the end of the First World War, the channel had remained watered, because it supplied the main line of the Shropshire Union Canal. In the period after the Second World War, there was growing interest in using the canals for leisure cruising, and the pioneer [[L. T. C. Rolt|Tom Rolt]] attempted to cruise the canal in 1947.{{sfn |Davies |2005 |p=84}} Rolt's boat was ''Cressy'', which had been converted at Frankton to steam power, and on which Rolt had sailed westwards from Frankton Junction with Kyrle Willans after its conversion in 1930. At that time they had failed to reach Pontcysyllte.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=36}} On this occasion, he was joined by a small cruiser named ''Heron'', crewed by the Grundy family from Liverpool. The state of the canal was poor, and several of the locks were disintegrating, but despite low water levels and thick weed growth, both boats eventually reached Ellesmere. They then found that the water supply had been cut off due to a broken culvert near Chirk. After several weeks of being stranded, Rolt talked to the Chester office, and they arranged for water to be let down the canal, to enable the boats to return to Hurleston.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=37-38}} On a second attempt two years later, Rolt and his wife reached Pontcysyllte,{{sfn |Davies |2005 |p=84}} which they crossed accompanied by the actor [[Hugh Griffith]] and his wife Gunde. The Rolts moored for nearly three months just beyond the aqueduct, near the site where their boat had been built during the First World War.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=36,56}} In August they were joined by Roger Calvert and his family, who were attempting to reach the top of the canal in a home-made boat, which was pulled by a donkey. The Rolts travelled with them for part of the journey.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=58}} Edward Wilson, another canal enthusiast, reached Trevor in his boat in 1952, and the [[Inland Waterways Association]] held a rally at Llangollen later that year.{{sfn |Davies |2005 |p=84}}\n\nBy 1954, the Llangollen Canal was in a curious position. Under the terms of the LMSR Act of abandonment, obtained in 1944, navigation had been abandoned, but the right to sell water had been retained. This was to be for a period of ten years, during which those who bought the water were required to make alternative arrangements, which they failed to do. Since the nationalisation of the canals in 1948, the canal had been managed by the [[British Transport Commission]], who had to obtain Parliamentary approval to extend this arrangement. Meanwhile, a number of pleasure boats had ventured onto the canal, and there was a growing campaign to reopen the canal for navigation. A committee to spearhead this had been formed, and was chaired by the clerk for Wrexham Rural District Council, Trevor Williams. More than thirty other organisations were supporting the move, including the British Travel and Holidays Association.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=110-111}}\n\nIn 1955, the Board of Survey, a committee chaired by Lord Rusholme, had produced a report on the future of the canals under the control of the British Transport Commission, which they had divided into three categories. There were {{convert|336|mi|km}} of 'waterways to be developed', another {{convert|994|mi|km}} of 'waterways to be retained', and finally {{convert|771|mi|km}} of 'waterways having insufficient commercial prospects to justify their retention for navigation'. The Llangollen Canal was placed in the latter category, since it was still officially disused.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |pp=116-117}} This was followed in 1958 by the Bowes Report, which suggested that the first two categories should be classified as Class A and Class B waterways, with Class B waterways put back into good working order and retained for 25 years, to attract private investment. The Llangollen Canal was still in the final category, but the report at least suggested that there should be a right of appeal against closure, and gave the first hints that such canals could be retained because of their social value for recreation.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=163}}\n\nHugh McKnight, the editor of the Inland Waterways Association's ''Bulletin'', wrote an optimistic report in 1966, pointing to the achievements of the first 20 years of the organisation's existence, mentioning the changes in public opinion concerning the canals, and pointing particularly to the growth in leisure use on the Llangollen Canal and the Oxford Canal.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=229}} Official attitudes changed, and the provisions of the Transport Act 1968 placed the canals under the control of the [[British Waterways Board]], who were tasked with maintaining, developing and running them for the benefit of users.{{sfn |Bolton |1990 |p=233}} The whole of the branch from Hurleston Junction to Llantisilio, just below Horseshoe Falls, was listed in the Act as a cruising waterway, meaning that its future was no longer in jeopardy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1968/73/schedule/12 |title=Transport Act 1968 |publisher=The National Archives |at=Schedule 12 Part II Cruising Waterways |year=1968 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> As use by leisure craft grew, the \"Llangollen Branch of the Shropshire Union\" became popular due to its aqueducts and scenery. The canal was later renamed the Llangollen Canal, becoming one of the most popular canals for holidaymakers in Britain.{{sfn |Mosse |2010 |p=248}} The name is now used for the entire route from Hurleston to Llangollen, even though it was never described in this way during its commercial life.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=17}} It is not entirely clear when the name was first applied, since it was listed as the \"Welsh Canal\", a branch of the Shropshire Union, in 1985. At that time, potential boaters were advised that the canal was a water supply channel, and that they should submit an application containing full details and dimensions of their boat if they wanted to cruise on it. Nevertheless, they were instructed that British Waterways were keen to see leisure use of the canal, and that it could be quite congested in the summer season.{{sfn |Edwards |1985 |p=304}} Its origins as parts of two separate canals can be seen from the fact that the bridges are numbered from 1 at Hurleston to 70 at Rowsons Bridge, just past Frankton Junction. Continuing along the route to Llangollen, bridge numbering restarts at 1, while bridges 71 and upwards continue along what is now the Montgomery Canal, but was formerly the Ellesmere Branch to Llanymynech, where it joined the Montgomeryshire Canal.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=29,67}}\n\nA notable feature of the canal is the [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]], built by [[Thomas Telford]]. Opened in 1805, the aqueduct is more than {{convert|300|m}} long and {{convert|38|m}} above the valley floor. It has 19 stone arches, each with a 45-foot (14 metre) span. Another aqueduct carries the canal over the [[Ceiriog Valley|River Ceiriog]] at [[Chirk]], and there are tunnels nearby at Whitehouses, Chirk, and Ellesmere.\n\nThe canal also forms the boundary on two sides of the [[Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses NNR|Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses National Nature Reserve]]. In 2009 an eleven-mile section of the canal from Gledrid Bridge near Rhoswiel through to the [[Horseshoe Falls (Wales)|Horseshoe Falls]], which includes [[Chirk Aqueduct]] and [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]], was declared a [[World Heritage site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/visual_arts/architecture_and_design/article6594604.ece |title=Unesco names Pontcysyllte aqueduct as UK's latest World Heritage site |date=28 June 2009 |accessdate=12 January 2010 |newspaper=The Times |location=London}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Llangollen canal wharf.jpg|Llangollen canal wharf.\nFile:pontcysyllte aqueduct arp.jpg|A [[narrowboat]] traverses the [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]].\n</gallery>\n\n== Route ==\n=== Hurleston to Frankton Junction ===\n{{Ellesmere Canal Hurleston Branch map|Hurleston to Frankton Junction}}\n\nThe canal at Hurleston Junction rises from the Shropshire Union Canal main line, through four adjacent locks, with a total rise of {{convert|34|ft|3|in|m}}.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=18}} The canal had been an early pioneer in the use of iron lock gates, instead of the more traditional wooden ones, and this material was first used on the locks at Frankton in 1819.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=179}} The four locks here have a mixture of wooden and metal gates. All were built by the engineer J Fletcher around 1805. Lock 1 has metal lower gates, and a wooden upper gate, while gates at both ends of lock 2 are made of metal. The metal gates on both locks were replaced in 1974.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138544 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 1 (east)}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num=1136468 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 2}}</ref> Locks 3 and 4 have a single metal gate at the upper end, and wooden mitre gates at the lower end. Like many of the structures on the canal, they are [[grade II listed]] structures.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1330142 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 3}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num=1136476 |desc=Hurleston Lock No. 4 (west)}}</ref>\n\nBeside the locks is Hurleston Reservoir, which has a capacity of {{convert|85|e6impgal|Ml}}. It is supplied with water that flows down the canal from Horseshoe Falls at Llantisilio, and is used both for drinking water and to supply the main line of the Shropshire Union Canal.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=19}}\nWater enters it through a side channel with sluices and a weir, just above lock number 4. The treatment works on the west bank is now operated by United Utilities, and was given a \u00a36 million upgrade in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mgf.ltd.uk/case-study/case-study-water-treatment-works-at-hurleston/ |title=Case Study - Hurleston Water Treatment Works |publisher=MGF |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nJust beyond the A534 Wrexham Road bridge is the entrance to Swanley Bridge Marina, on the west bank of the canal. It has moorings for over 300 boats, and is situated in {{convert|250|acre|ha}} of farmland, which includes a {{convert|7|acre|ha|adj=on}} wood with nature trails. It opened in September 2006, and was built in response to a document published by British Waterways in the spring of that year, which outlined development opportunities for farmers and landowners adjacent to the canal.<ref>{{cite book |title=Llangollen Canal Marina |publisher=Waterways World |date=November 2006 |issn=0309-1422}}</ref>\n\nThe two Swanley locks raise the level of the canal by another {{convert|12|ft|10|in|m}},{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=18}} and by the upper lock is the grade II listed Swanley Hall, a red-brick farmhouse parts of which date from the early 16th century.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138575 |desc=Swanley Hall |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> Baddiley Hall, which has three storeys and an attic, and dates from the late 17th century, is set some distance back from the canal.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138585 |desc=Baddiley Hall |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> In its grounds is the [[grade I listed]] parish church of St. Michael, the chancel of which dates from 1308, while the nave dates from 1811.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1138586 |desc=Church of St. Michael |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> Both are separated from the canal by a [[scheduled monument]] site, containing the earthworks and buried remains of an abandoned medieval village.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1018822 |desc=Medieval village remains east of Baddiley Hall |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> The three Baddiley locks follow, with a combined rise of {{convert|19|ft|8|in|m}}.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=18}}\n \n[[File:Bridge \"Wrenbury Lift ^2\" - geograph.org.uk - 336435.jpg|thumb|left|Wrenbury Church lift bridge is one of three in the village.]]\nAfter passing Wrenbury Hall, on the west bank, the canal turns to the west, and is crossed by the Wrenbury Church lift bridge, the first of three lift-bridges in the village.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=20-21}} It is formed of timber planks fixed between wooden beams, and the bridge deck is hinged at the northern end. A weighted counterbalance allows the bridge to be opened, and the structure is [[grade II* listed]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1357482 |desc=Wrenbury Church lift bridge |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> [[Wrenbury]] lift bridge, No. 20, is automated, with push-button controls. It is operated by use of a British Waterways key, and involves closing barriers and stopping traffic on a sometimes-busy road. Wrenbury Wharf is next to the bridge, where the former mill building has been reused by a boatyard, and a nearby warehouse has become a pub.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=20}}\n\nAt [[Grindley Brook]], the canal was crossed by the defunct [[Whitchurch and Tattenhall Railway]]. The railway and the nearby [[Grindley Brook Halt railway station]] closed in 1957,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shropshirehistory.com/railways/stations.htm|title=Stations|work=Shropshire History|accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> and goods traffic ceased in 1963, but the massive embankments and bridge remain. Immediately afterwards, the canal passes through three locks and a three-chamber staircase lock, attended during summer months by a [[lock keeper]]. The six locks raise the level of the canal by {{convert|38|ft|11|in|m}}. After another mile (1.6&nbsp;km), there is a lift bridge just before the entrance to the Whitchurch Arm, which served the town of [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]]. Part of it remains open, and is used for moorings.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=22-23}} The section from the main line to Sherryman's Bridge was opened on 6 July 1808, and in 1811 a further extension into the town reached Castle Well.{{sfn |Hadfield |1985 |p=178}} The arm remained closed when the canal reopened in the 1950s, but Whitchurch Town Council looked at ways of bringing boats back into the town in the early 1980s{{sfn |Squires |2008 |p=113}} and the embryonic [[Whitchurch Waterway Trust]] was formed in 1986, with the aim of reopening the arm, of which around {{convert|0.75|mi|km}} was left, the rest having been built over in the 1950s.{{sfn |Squires |2008 |p=113}} This was achieved in October 1993, and the trust are hopeful that a new route into the town can be constructed.{{sfn |Squires |2008 |pp=118, 134}}\n\nBetween bridges 42 and 47, the canal skirts the eastern edge and then passes through and the southern edge of Whixall Moss, part of the [[Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses National Nature Reserve]]. With a combined area of nearly {{convert|2500|acre|km2}}, they form the third largest area of raised peat bog in the United Kingdom. The reserve is also a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]], a European [[Special Area of Conservation]] and a Wetland of International Importance under the [[Ramsar site|Ramsar Convention]]. The bogs were drained using powers enshrined in Enclosure Acts dating from 1777 and 1823, and further drainage took place when the canal was built in 1804, and again in 1863 when a railway was built along the north-western margins. Commercial peat cutting using mechanised cutters began in 1968, but extraction ceased in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/sites/www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/files/NNR_Fenns_Whixall_leaflet.pdf |title=Fenn's, Whixall and Bettisfield Mosses National Nature Reserve |publisher=Natural England |pp=4\u20135 |accessdate=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313214315/http://www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/sites/www.iucn-uk-peatlandprogramme.org/files/NNR_Fenns_Whixall_leaflet.pdf |archive-date=13 March 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe technical difficulties of cutting a canal through Whixall Moss were many, but Jessop and Telford decided on a direct route across the moss, rather than building a bypass that skirted round the edge of the area. The water table in the Moss was lowered by drainage and a raft was constructed, on which the canal was built.<ref name=sucs>{{cite web |url=http://www.shropshireunion.org.uk/the-canals/early-history |title=Early History of the Shropshire Union Canals |publisher=Shropshire Union Canal Society |accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> The canal had to float across the peat, and the engineers understood that regular maintenance of this section would be a requirement for many years. They employed a team of navvies to build up the banks with more clay on a continuous basis, who became known as the Whixall Moss Gang.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/england/shropshire/article_2.shtml |title=The Whixall Moss Gang (2) |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales / BBC |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> Clay was obtained from the clay pit which became Whixall Marina, and was transferred to the work site in horse-drawn barges. Men were employed on this work from 1804 until 1960, working five and a half days a week, and became the longest serving group of navvies ever to work on the British canals. In the 1960s, the engineering issues that created the work were solved, and they were all laid off.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/england/shropshire/article_3.shtml |title=The Whixall Moss Gang (3) |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales / BBC |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> The solution adopted to prevent the canal sinking further into the peat was to underpin the whole section with steel piling.<ref name=sucs/>\n\nAdjacent to bridge 46 is Whixall Moss Junction leading to the Prees Branch.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=25}} Two breaches of the canal have occurred near Whixall in recent years. The first was in 2004 at Hampton Bank, near bridge 50, when badgers burrowed into the bank, causing it to fail. The animals were also implicated in a breach some {{convert|440|yd|m}} to the east of Cornhill Bridge 47, which occurred in late 2009. The bank failed as new piling was being driven in, but had previously been weakened by burrowing.{{sfn |Minifie |2010 |p=46}}\n\nAs the canal approaches Ellesmere, it passes a series of [[Mere (lake)|meres]]. Cole Mere is very close to the south bank of the canal, but at a lower level. Blake Mere is on the towpath side, with only the towpath separating it from the canal in places. Both are surrounded by woods, and the canal is fringed by oak trees, many planted by the Shropshire Union Company to ensure that they had supplies of timber to replace their fleet of wooden boats as that became necessary. At the far end of Blake Mere is the short Ellesmere Tunnel, just {{convert|87|yd|m}} long, and beyond that the market town of [[Ellesmere, Shropshire|Ellesmere]]. A short branch leads into the town,{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=26-27}} at the end of which is a three-storey, red brick warehouse, dating from the early 19th century, which is grade II listed.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1055499 |desc=Canal Warehouse |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> At the junction is a Canal and River Trust maintenance depot, housed in a series of buildings which are all grade II* listed. The complex includes Beech House, the offices of the Ellesmere Canal Company from 1806, but now converted into flats. The range of buildings form the best-preserved canal maintenance yard in Britain.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1176445 |desc=Beech House Canal Maintenance Depot |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> The former stables and stores, which are now used as offices, include an exceptionally early example of a covered dry dock, in which barges were built and repaired. It predates the better known examples of covered slips at the naval dockyards of [[HMNB Devonport|Devonport]] and [[Chatham Dockyard|Chatham]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1366122 |desc=Canal Maintenance Depot South East Side |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe canal also passes though [[Burland]], [[Quoisley Bridge]], and [[Bettisfield]].\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Prees Branch=== <!-- This is linked to by a redirect \"Prees Branch\" -->\n{{Prees Branch Canal Route Map}}\nThe Prees Arm of the canal was originally intended to reach [[Prees]], but only the first {{convert|3.75|mi|km}} were constructed, terminating at [[Quina Brook]]. Much of the ground through which it passed is formed of peat.{{sfn |Edwards |1985 |p=305}} Today it is only open for 7 [[furlong]]s (1.4&nbsp;km), with two lift bridges, to a [[marina]] at the end of the navigable part; beyond that, another {{convert|0.62|mi|km|0}}, as far as Waterloo Bridge,{{sfn |Edwards |1985 |p=310}} is partially watered and forms the [[Prees Branch Canal Nature Reserve]]. The remaining {{convert|2|mi|km}} is dry, but can be followed in the landscape as most of it is marked by trees growing along its course.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/@52.8872502,-2.7265292,1163m/data=!3m1!1e3 |title=Satellite view |publisher=Google maps}}</ref> The towpath is on the eastern bank from the junction to Dobson's Bridge, and then crosses over to the other side, where it remained to the end of the canal at Quina Brook.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=25}}\n\nNext to the junction is a toll-keeper's cottage dating from around 1800, the time of the construction of the canal. It has since been reused as a farmhouse.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237205 |desc=Roving Bridge House |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> Allman's Bridge dates from the construction of the canal, although there have been some later repairs to the structure. The wooden decking is opened by a counterweight and chains.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237206 |desc=Allman's Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> It was one of the last manual lift bridges to be converted to hydraulic operation in 2010. Nearby is a single arched [[squinch]] bridge, again dating from the early 1800s and constructed in red bricks. It crosses a drainage ditch, probably associated with the drainage of Whixall Moss, which passes under the canal at this point.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237334 |desc=Squinch bridge over stream north east of Allmans Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> Starks Bridge is another wooden lift bridge, and as well as being grade II* listed, is a scheduled ancient monument.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1244333 |desc=Starks Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> It is a rare example of a skewed lift bridge.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p-24}} Dobson's Bridge, a fixed [[humpback bridge]] made of red bricks with an elliptical arch, was classified in 1987 as a Grade Il [[listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237207 |desc=Dobson's Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the navigable section is Whixall Marina, which was constructed on the site of some clay pits, which for many years supplied clay used for puddling of the canals.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=24}} From 2017 to 2018, the marina had been refurbished with the addition of a waterside cafe, car park and new shower and toilet facilities. It is also near the famous Whixall Moss which is used by many walkers. On the nature reserve section, Boodles Bridge is of similar construction and date to Dobson's Bridge.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1237348 |desc=Boodles Bridge |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> At the far end of the canal are the remains of two groups of limekilns, the main group consisting of four kilns built of red brick and sandstone rubble. They were built at the same time as the branch was constructed.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1236700 |desc=Limekilns |accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Prees-branch.png|Old map showing the complete branch to Quina Brook\nFile:WhixallMarinaEvening.jpg|Evening over Whixall Marina\n</gallery>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Frankton Junction to Trevor Basin ===\n{{Ellesmere Canal Main Line map|Frankton Junction to Trevor Basin}}\nAt Frankton Junction the [[Montgomery Canal]], which is partially restored, heads southwards. For historic reasons the bridge numbering continues down the Montgomery Canal and a second bridge numbering series for the Llangollen Canal begins with Rowson's Bridge (which is numbered both 1W and 70). The \"W\" addition was part of a Minimum Safety Standards scheme instigated by British Waterways, to avoid possible confusion, especially for emergency services, of having different bridges on the same canal with the same number. British Waterways consulted with the Inland Waterways Association and the Shropshire Union Canal Society before finally deciding to add the \"W\", and at the same time as the numbers were altered, it ensured that all bridges carried a number on both sides. The work was due to be completed by July 2008, but there were delays due to manufacturing difficulties with the new castings.{{sfn |Minifie |2008 |p=56}}\n\nThe Llangollen Canal passes through [[Hindford]], [[St Martin's, Shropshire|Saint Martin's]], [[Preesgweene]], [[Chirk Bank]], [[Chirk]] and [[Froncysyllte]], and includes the [[Chirk Aqueduct]], the [[Chirk Tunnel]] and the [[Pontcysyllte Aqueduct]].\n\n<gallery perrow=\"3\">\nFile:FranktonJunction-01s.jpg|[[Frankton Junction]]\nFile:NewMartonBottomLock 01s.jpg|New Marton Bottom Lock\nFile:NewMartonTopLock 01s.jpg|New Marton Top Lock\nFile:Y Waun AqueductWales.JPG|[[Chirk Aqueduct]]\nFile:Chirk tunnel.jpg|[[Chirk Tunnel]]\nFile:TrevorBasin-01s.jpg|[[Trevor Basin]]\n</gallery>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Trevor Basin to Horseshoe Falls ===\n{{Ellesmere Canal Llangollen Branch map|Trevor Basin to Horseshoe Falls}}\nThis section was built as a navigable feeder and is both shallow and narrow. Some sections near Llangollen are too narrow for boats to pass each other and it is necessary to scout ahead to check for oncoming boats. Navigation should not be attempted by boats with a draught of more than {{convert|21|in|cm}}.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=30}} A number of breaches had occurred on this final section over many years, and in the early 1980s, British Waterways initiated a programme to resolve this issue. Parts of it were rebuilt with a concrete lining, which included a waterproof membrane to retain the water, and a system of drainage pipes underneath the bed, to prevent water building up and damaging the construction.{{sfn |Goss |2009 |p=84}}\n\nNavigation by powered craft is prohibited beyond the entrance to Llangollen Marina and the final section is used only by horse drawn trip boats. The current boats maintain a long tradition, which was first offered to visitors in 1884.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=33}} The towpath beside the feeder is in good condition, and walkers can reach the weir at Horseshoe Falls.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |pp=33-34}} [[British Waterways]] maintains a gravel [[shoal]] immediately upstream of the marina entrance past Llangollen Wharf. This maintains a draught which most [[narrowboat]]s cannot pass, but which is passable by the shallow draughted trip boats.\n\nIn 2005, a marina was constructed by British Waterways, just upstream from Llangollen Wharf, to relieve the acute shortage of casual moorings, and provides 33 berths. About {{convert|100|yd|m}} downstream of the wharf there are about a dozen visitor moorings complete with individual electricity and water pedestals at each. Similar pedestals have also been installed at the marina berths. Mooring in Llangollen is restricted to 48 hours, and a charge is made both at the marina and the visitor moorings, which are below bridge 45.{{sfn |Nicholson |2006 |p=34}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Transport|Cheshire}}\n*[[Canals of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[History of the British canal system]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Bolton |first=David\n  |title=Race Against Time\n  |date=1990\n  |publisher=Methuen\n  |isbn=978-0-413-63470-2\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Davies |first=Robert\n  |title=Llangollen and Pontcysyllte\n  |date=August 2005\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Denton |first=John Horsley\n  |title=Montgomershire Canal and the Llanymynech Branch of the Ellesmere Canal\n  |year=1984\n  |publisher=Lapal Publications\n  |isbn=978-0-9509238-1-9\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book \n  |first=L A |last=Edwards\n  |title=Inland Waterways of Great Britain (6th Ed)\n  |publisher=Imray Laurie Norie and Wilson\n  |year=1985\n  |isbn=978-0-85288-081-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Goss |first=Keith\n  |title=WW Guide to the Llangollen Canal\n  |date=July 2009\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book \n  |first=Charles |last=Hadfield \n  |title=The Canals of the West Midlands \n  |publisher=David and Charles \n  |year=1985 \n  |isbn=978-0-7153-8644-6\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |first=Hugh |last=McKnight\n  |title=The Shell Book of Inland Waterways\n  |publisher=[[David & Charles]]\n  |year=1987\n  |isbn=978-0-7153-8239-4\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Minifie |first=Michael\n  |title=Renumbered Bridges\n  |date=December 2008\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Minifie |first=Michael\n  |title=Llangollen Canal\n  |date=January 2010\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |issn=0309-1422\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |first=Jonathan |last=Mosse\n  |title=Waterways of Britain\n  |publisher=Times Books\n  |year=2010\n  |isbn=978-0-00-787363-0\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |last=Nicholson\n  |authorlink=Nicholson Guides\n  |title=Nicholson Guides Vol 4: Four Counties and the Welsh Canals\n  |publisher=Harper Collins\n  |year=2006\n  |isbn=978-0-00-721112-8\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |last=Waterways World\n  |title=Canal Guide 2 \u2013 Llangollen and Montgomery Canals\n  |year=2005\n  |publisher=Waterways World\n  |isbn=978-1-870002-89-9\n  |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610093308/http://www.northwalesborderlands.co.uk/explore-north-wales-borderlands/heritage.aspx Llangollen Canal] \u2013 North Wales Borderlands website\n\n{{Canals of Britain}}\n\n{{Coord|52.9722|N|3.1711|W|display=title|region:GB_type:river}}\n\n[[Category:Llangollen Canal| ]]\n[[Category:Canals in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Canals in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Canals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Shropshire Union Canal]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Denbighshire]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHurleston to Frankton Junction:Typo fixing, replaced: passes though  \u2192  passes through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Llangollen_Canal"}
{"title_page": "Warren McArthur", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Warren McArthur\n| caption        =  \n| nationality    = American\n| birth_name     = Warren McArthur, Jr.\n| birth_date     = 1885\n| birth_place    = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date     = December 1961\n| death_place    = [[New York, New York]], U.S.\n| alma mater     = [[Cornell University]]\n| occupation     = [[Industrial design]]er \n| known_for      = Streamline design, art deco design, aluminum tubular furniture, military and civilian aircraft seating\n| spouse         = Lorraine McArthur\n| children       = Warren McArthur, III    \n| relatives        = [[Albert Chase McArthur]]<br>Charles McArthur   \n}}\n\n[[File:IMAGE overall, 1990.95.jpg. Brooklyn Museum photograph, 2004.jpg|thumb|IMAGE overall, 1990.95.jpg. Brooklyn Museum photograph, 2004]]\n'''Warren McArthur''' (1885\u20131961) was an American industrial and furniture designer who specialized in aluminum tubular furniture during the 1930s. \n\n== Early life and career ==\nWarren McArthur, Jr. was born in Chicago, Illinois to Warren McArthur, Sr., a successful businessman, and Minnie Jewel McArthur.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's Return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#56021dfed9a5 |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] was a friend of the McArthur family. In 1892, Wright designed the house for the McArthur family, located in Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur House |url=https://flwright.org/researchexplore/wrightbuildings/warrenmcarthurhouse |website=Frank Lloyd Wright Trust |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMcArthur attended Cornell University where he studied engineering.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> In January 1912, McArthur announced his engagement to his future wife Lorraine Peaslee of Dubuque, Iowa.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Alumni Notes |journal=The Cornell Alumni News |date=January 31, 1912 |volume=14 |pages=202}}</ref> \n\nShortly after graduating from Cornell, in 1912, McArthur received a patent for the short-globe lamp, which he sold to the Dietz Lantern Company for $2,000.00.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The following year, McArthur moved to Phoenix, Arizona with his brother, Charles, and formed the McArthur Brothers Mercantile Company to sell automobiles for Dodge.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The brothers also formed KFAD, currently [[KTAR (AM)]], the first radio station in Arizona, which began broadcasting in Phoenix on June 21, 1922.<ref>{{cite web |title=KFAD-KREP-KTAR-History |url=http://www.smecc.org/kfad_-_krep_-_ktar_-_history.htm |website=Southwest Museum of Engineering, Communications and Computation. |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In the mid-1920s, the brothers converted a Dodge truck into a RV, that they called the Wonderbus, and gave tours of the Tucson area to tourists, including [[Sinclair Lewis]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#56021dfed9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> On January 4, 1926, Warren McArthur filed a patent for the RV design, called Touring and Camping Road Vehicle, and the patent was granted on March 10, 1931.<ref>{{cite web |title=US1796112A |url=https://patentimages.storage.googleapis.com/c6/6b/3d/86e242f17caf29/US1796112.pdf |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career in furniture design  ==\nIn the late 1920s, McArthur began his career as an industrial designer by creating furniture for the [[Arizona Biltmore Hotel]], which was designed by his brother [[Albert Chase McArthur]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Artifact Spotlight: Warren McArthur Furniture |url=https://www.richmond.com/discover-richmond/artifact-spotlight-warren-mcarthur-furniture/article_1da3a6e9-e136-5d24-9d19-71e72394f874.html |website=Richmond Times-Dispatch |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]], the Arizona Biltmore failed, and McArthur moved to Los Angeles, California to create a furniture fabrication company.<ref>{{cite news |title=ANTIQUES; Rediscovered: Early Master of Metal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |publisher=The New York Times|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref> In the early 1930s, aluminum became a popular industrial design material, and McArthur developed a specialization in designing and making aluminum tubular furniture, including chairs, tables, sofas, lamps, and ashtrays. \n\nMcArthur soon began to receive commissions from prominent architects. [[Paul Williams (architect)]] commissioned McArthur to design 30 pieces of aluminum furniture for the Cord family who owned the [[Cord automobile]] company.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news |title=Id. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |accessdate=March 22, 2020|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref> He was also commissioned to make aluminum furniture for architect [[Rudolph Schindler]]'s design for [[Sardi's]] restaurant location in Los Angeles.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> [[File:Warren mcarthur per warren mcarthur corporation, sedia, rome NY 1936 ca.jpg|thumb|Warren mcarthur per warren mcarthur corporation, sedia, rome NY 1936 ca]] \n\nSo too, McArthur's aluminum furniture was popular with Hollywood stars and producers of the 1930s. His clients included [[Jack L. Warner]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Fredric March]], and [[Clark Gable]].<ref name=\"March 22, 2020\">{{cite news |title=ANTIQUES; Rediscovered: Early Master of Metal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=New York Times|date=27 August 1999 |last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref> \n\nIn 1932, McArthur left Los Angeles and established the Warren McArthur Corp. in Rome, New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#60fe151ad9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> He also set up a sales office and showroom in New York City at 1 Park Avenue in 1933.<ref>{{cite news |title=Id. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |accessdate=March 23, 2020|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref>  \n\nMcArthur's success grew during his time in New York and his furniture \"graced the most sophisticated homes, stores and offices in the country\" during the decade.<ref>{{cite web |title=Id. |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#56021dfed9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> His commissions included [[Union Pacific Railroad]] cars, [[Cunard]] passenger waiting lounges, [[Chrysler]] executive offices, and [[Marshall Field's]] department store hair salons.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> \n\nDuring 1937, the Warren McArthur Corp. purchased and moved to a 40,000 square feet factory in Bantam, Connecticut.<ref>{{cite news |title=LARGE PLANT SOLD IN BANTAM, CONN.; Warren McArthur Corp. Buys Factory With 40,000 Square Feet of Floor Space |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/12/14/archives/large-plant-sold-in-bantam-conn-warren-mcarthur-corp-buys-factory.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=New York Times |date=December 14, 1937}}</ref> In 1940, the [[Virginia State Library]] purchased McArthur aluminum furniture for its new art deco building, currently the [[Patrick Henry Building]], which remained in the building until the library moved to a new location in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=Richmond Times-Dispatch |url=https://www.richmond.com/discover-richmond/artifact-spotlight-warren-mcarthur-furniture/article_1da3a6e9-e136-5d24-9d19-71e72394f874.html |website=Artifact Spotlight: Warren McArthur Furniture |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In 1941, McArthur designed furniture for the [[SS Milwaukee Clipper]], which still contains the original McArthur furniture.<ref>{{cite web |title=Main Lounge |url=https://www.milwaukeeclipper.com/?page_id=853 |website=www.milwaukeeclipper.com |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Warren McArthur Chair Circa 1938.jpg|thumb|Circa 1938]] \n\n== Furniture construction ==\nMcArthur's furniture was made in limited production because of the painstaking construction and expensive materials used.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's Return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#66cde99fd9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> McArthur patented a technique to provide rigidity and strength to his aluminum tubular furniture, aluminum being a weak metal. McArthur placed supporting steel rods inside the hollow aluminum tubes of his furniture.\n<ref>{{cite news |title=Furniture Patent |url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US2035489A/en?inventor=Jr+Warren+Mcarthur |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=March 5, 1934}}</ref> McArthur attached the tubes and inner rods together with interchangeable joints that were visible and capped with attractive nut coverings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Furniture Patent |url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US2035489A/en?inventor=Jr+Warren+Mcarthur |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=March 5, 1934}}</ref> The furniture was then polished and given a finish that resembled matte silver. \n\n== Wartime production and later career ==\nWith the start of [[World War II]], aluminum was restricted to war needs. The Warren McArthur Corp. was asked by the United States government to make aluminum aircraft seats for military airplanes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bantam's World War II |url=https://hiddeninplainsightblog.com/tag/warren-mcarthur/ |website=Hidden in Plain Sight |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> McArthur produced the majority of aircraft seating for military planes during the war.<ref>{{cite news |title=ANTIQUES; Rediscovered: Early Master of Metal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |accessdate=March 20, 2020|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref>\n\nMcArthur continued to produce airplane seats after the war, however, his company closed in 1948.<ref>{{cite web |title=The sad story of Warren McArthur |url=https://observer-reporter.com/lifestyles/the-sad-story-of-warren-mcarthur/article_24ade1f0-8de9-5269-bf9f-e4faef0d0de5.html |website=Observer-Reporter |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> During the 1950s, McArthur founded Mayfair Industries in Yonkers, New York and continued to produce furniture, including a popular folding chair design, until he retired.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur Bio |url=https://collection.cooperhewitt.org/people/18051607/bio#ch |website=Cooper Hewitt |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcArthur died in 1961 in New York City.\n\n== Legacy ==\nLargely forgotten by the 1970s, McArthur's furniture was rediscovered in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite journal |title=New York Magazine |date=February 5, 1996 |page=40}}</ref> During that decade, [[Dolce & Gabbana]] used McArthur furniture in its ad campaign.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Id.}}</ref>\n\nWarren McArthur furniture is now highly sought by collectors and included in numerous museum collections, including the [[Brooklyn Museum]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Side Chair |url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/objects/1944 |website=Brooklyn Museum |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Table |url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/211600 |website=Los Angeles County Museum of Art |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Armchair |url=https://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/296723.html |website=Philadelphia Museum of Art |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> the  [[Art Institute of Chicago]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Side Chair |url=https://www.artic.edu/artists/90543/warren-mcarthur |website=Art Institute of Chicago |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> the [[Virginia Museum of Fine Arts]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Circular Table |url=https://www.vmfa.museum/piction/6027262-15842914/ |website=Virginia Museum of Fine Arts |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum]].<ref name=CH>{{cite web |url=https://collection.cooperhewitt.org/objects/420556859/ |title=1044-A Armchair, ca. 1935 |author=Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum |accessdate=24 March 2020 |publisher=Smithsonian Institution}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McArthur, Walter}}\n[[Category:American industrial designers]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:American furniture designers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Cornell University College of Engineering alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Warren McArthur\n| caption        =  \n| nationality    = American\n| birth_name     = Warren McArthur, Jr.\n| birth_date     = 1885\n| birth_place    = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date     = December 1961\n| death_place    = [[New York, New York]], U.S.\n| alma mater     = [[Cornell University]]\n| occupation     = [[Industrial design]]er \n| known_for      = Streamline aluminum furniture, art deco design, military and civilian aircraft seating\n| spouse         = Lorraine McArthur\n| children       = Warren McArthur, III    \n| relatives        = [[Albert Chase McArthur]]<br>Charles McArthur   \n}}\n\n[[File:IMAGE overall, 1990.95.jpg. Brooklyn Museum photograph, 2004.jpg|thumb|IMAGE overall, 1990.95.jpg. Brooklyn Museum photograph, 2004]]\n'''Warren McArthur''' (1885\u20131961) was an American industrial and furniture designer who specialized in aluminum furniture during the 1930s. \n\n== Early life and career ==\nWarren McArthur, Jr. was born in Chicago, Illinois to Warren McArthur, Sr., a successful businessman, and Minnie Jewel McArthur.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's Return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#56021dfed9a5 |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] was a friend of the McArthur family. In 1892, Wright designed the house for the McArthur family, located in Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur House |url=https://flwright.org/researchexplore/wrightbuildings/warrenmcarthurhouse |website=Frank Lloyd Wright Trust |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMcArthur attended Cornell University where he studied engineering.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> In January 1912, McArthur announced his engagement to his future wife Lorraine Peaslee of Dubuque, Iowa.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Alumni Notes |journal=The Cornell Alumni News |date=January 31, 1912 |volume=14 |pages=202}}</ref> \n\nShortly after graduating from Cornell, in 1912, McArthur received a patent for the short-globe lamp, which he sold to the Dietz Lantern Company for $2,000.00.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The following year, McArthur moved to Phoenix, Arizona with his brother, Charles, and formed the McArthur Brothers Mercantile Company to sell automobiles for Dodge.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The brothers also formed KFAD, currently [[KTAR (AM)]], the first radio station in Arizona, which began broadcasting in Phoenix on June 21, 1922.<ref>{{cite web |title=KFAD-KREP-KTAR-History |url=http://www.smecc.org/kfad_-_krep_-_ktar_-_history.htm |website=Southwest Museum of Engineering, Communications and Computation. |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In the mid-1920s, the brothers converted a Dodge truck into a RV, that they called the Wonderbus, and gave tours of the Tucson area to tourists, including [[Sinclair Lewis]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#56021dfed9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> On January 4, 1926, Warren McArthur filed a patent for the RV design, called Touring and Camping Road Vehicle, and the patent was granted on March 10, 1931.<ref>{{cite web |title=US1796112A |url=https://patentimages.storage.googleapis.com/c6/6b/3d/86e242f17caf29/US1796112.pdf |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career in furniture design  ==\nIn the late 1920s, McArthur began his career as an industrial designer by creating furniture for the [[Arizona Biltmore Hotel]], which was designed by his brother [[Albert Chase McArthur]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Artifact Spotlight: Warren McArthur Furniture |url=https://www.richmond.com/discover-richmond/artifact-spotlight-warren-mcarthur-furniture/article_1da3a6e9-e136-5d24-9d19-71e72394f874.html |website=Richmond Times-Dispatch |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]], the Arizona Biltmore failed, and McArthur moved to Los Angeles, California to create a furniture fabrication company.<ref>{{cite news |title=ANTIQUES; Rediscovered: Early Master of Metal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |publisher=The New York Times|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref> In the early 1930s, aluminum became a popular industrial design material, and McArthur developed a specialization in designing and making aluminum tubular furniture, including chairs, tables, sofas, lamps, and ashtrays. \n\nMcArthur soon began to receive commissions from prominent architects. [[Paul Williams (architect)]] commissioned McArthur to design 30 pieces of aluminum furniture for the Cord family who owned the [[Cord automobile]] company.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news |title=Id. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |accessdate=March 22, 2020|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref> He was also commissioned to make aluminum furniture for architect [[Rudolph Schindler]]'s design for [[Sardi's]] restaurant location in Los Angeles.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> [[File:Warren mcarthur per warren mcarthur corporation, sedia, rome NY 1936 ca.jpg|thumb|Warren mcarthur per warren mcarthur corporation, sedia, rome NY 1936 ca]] \n\nSo too, McArthur's aluminum furniture was popular with Hollywood stars and producers of the 1930s. His clients included [[Jack L. Warner]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Fredric March]], and [[Clark Gable]].<ref name=\"March 22, 2020\">{{cite news |title=ANTIQUES; Rediscovered: Early Master of Metal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=New York Times|date=27 August 1999 |last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref> \n\nIn 1932, McArthur left Los Angeles and established the Warren McArthur Corp. in Rome, New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#60fe151ad9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> He also set up a sales office and showroom in New York City at 1 Park Avenue in 1933.<ref>{{cite news |title=Id. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |accessdate=March 23, 2020|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref>  \n\nMcArthur's success grew during his time in New York and his furniture \"graced the most sophisticated homes, stores and offices in the country\" during the decade.<ref>{{cite web |title=Id. |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#56021dfed9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> His commissions included [[Union Pacific Railroad]] cars, [[Cunard]] passenger waiting lounges, [[Chrysler]] executive offices, and [[Marshall Field's]] department store hair salons.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> \n\nDuring 1937, the Warren McArthur Corp. purchased and moved to a 40,000 square feet factory in Bantam, Connecticut.<ref>{{cite news |title=LARGE PLANT SOLD IN BANTAM, CONN.; Warren McArthur Corp. Buys Factory With 40,000 Square Feet of Floor Space |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/12/14/archives/large-plant-sold-in-bantam-conn-warren-mcarthur-corp-buys-factory.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=New York Times |date=December 14, 1937}}</ref> In 1940, the [[Virginia State Library]] purchased McArthur aluminum furniture for its new art deco building, currently the [[Patrick Henry Building]], which remained in the building until the library moved to a new location in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=Richmond Times-Dispatch |url=https://www.richmond.com/discover-richmond/artifact-spotlight-warren-mcarthur-furniture/article_1da3a6e9-e136-5d24-9d19-71e72394f874.html |website=Artifact Spotlight: Warren McArthur Furniture |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In 1941, McArthur designed furniture for the [[SS Milwaukee Clipper]], which still contains the original McArthur furniture.<ref>{{cite web |title=Main Lounge |url=https://www.milwaukeeclipper.com/?page_id=853 |website=www.milwaukeeclipper.com |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Warren McArthur Chair Circa 1938.jpg|thumb|Circa 1938]] \n\n== Furniture construction ==\nMcArthur's furniture was made in limited production because of the painstaking construction and expensive materials used.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur's Return |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0209/6103174b.html#66cde99fd9a5 |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> McArthur patented a technique to provide rigidity and strength to his aluminum tubular furniture, aluminum being a weak metal. McArthur placed supporting steel rods inside the hollow aluminum tubes of his furniture.\n<ref>{{cite news |title=Furniture Patent |url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US2035489A/en?inventor=Jr+Warren+Mcarthur |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=March 5, 1934}}</ref> McArthur attached the tubes and inner rods together with interchangeable joints that were visible and capped with attractive nut coverings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Furniture Patent |url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US2035489A/en?inventor=Jr+Warren+Mcarthur |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=March 5, 1934}}</ref> The furniture was then polished and given a finish that resembled matte silver. \n\n== Wartime production and later career ==\nWith the start of [[World War II]], aluminum was restricted to war needs. The Warren McArthur Corp. was asked by the United States government to make aluminum aircraft seats for military airplanes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bantam's World War II |url=https://hiddeninplainsightblog.com/tag/warren-mcarthur/ |website=Hidden in Plain Sight |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> McArthur produced the majority of aircraft seating for military planes during the war.<ref>{{cite news |title=ANTIQUES; Rediscovered: Early Master of Metal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/27/arts/antiques-rediscovered-early-master-of-metal.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 August 1999 |accessdate=March 20, 2020|last1=Moonan |first1=Wendy }}</ref>\n\nMcArthur continued to produce airplane seats after the war, however, his company closed in 1948.<ref>{{cite web |title=The sad story of Warren McArthur |url=https://observer-reporter.com/lifestyles/the-sad-story-of-warren-mcarthur/article_24ade1f0-8de9-5269-bf9f-e4faef0d0de5.html |website=Observer-Reporter |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> During the 1950s, McArthur founded Mayfair Industries in Yonkers, New York and continued to produce furniture, including a popular folding chair design, until he retired.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warren McArthur Bio |url=https://collection.cooperhewitt.org/people/18051607/bio#ch |website=Cooper Hewitt |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcArthur died in 1961 in New York City.\n\n== Legacy ==\nLargely forgotten by the 1970s, McArthur's furniture was rediscovered in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite journal |title=New York Magazine |date=February 5, 1996 |page=40}}</ref> During that decade, [[Dolce & Gabbana]] used McArthur furniture in its ad campaign.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Id.}}</ref>\n\nWarren McArthur furniture is now highly sought by collectors and included in numerous museum collections, including the [[Brooklyn Museum]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Side Chair |url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/objects/1944 |website=Brooklyn Museum |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Table |url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/211600 |website=Los Angeles County Museum of Art |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Armchair |url=https://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/296723.html |website=Philadelphia Museum of Art |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> the  [[Art Institute of Chicago]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Side Chair |url=https://www.artic.edu/artists/90543/warren-mcarthur |website=Art Institute of Chicago |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> the [[Virginia Museum of Fine Arts]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Circular Table |url=https://www.vmfa.museum/piction/6027262-15842914/ |website=Virginia Museum of Fine Arts |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum]].<ref name=CH>{{cite web |url=https://collection.cooperhewitt.org/objects/420556859/ |title=1044-A Armchair, ca. 1935 |author=Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum |accessdate=24 March 2020 |publisher=Smithsonian Institution}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McArthur, Walter}}\n[[Category:American industrial designers]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:American furniture designers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Cornell University College of Engineering alumni]]\n", "name_user": "841tray", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warren_McArthur"}
{"title_page": "Grunwaldzka street in Bydgoszcz", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Grunwaldzka street\n| marker_image            = Bydgoszcz\n| native_name             = {{lang-pl|Ulica Grunwaldzka w Bydgoszczy}}\n| alternate_name          =\n| image                   = File:Ul Grunwaldzka 16-26 Bydg 2008e.jpg\n| image_size              = 250 px\n| image_map               = File:Bydgoszcz ul Grunwaldzka.png\n| caption                 = View of historic facades on Grunwaldzka street\n| map_size                = 250 px\n| map_caption             = Grunwaldzka Street highlighted on a Bydgoszcz map\n| map_alt                 =\n| other_name              = \n| former_names            =  \n| part_of                 = \n| namesake                = [[Battle of Grunwald]]\n| type                    =\n| owner                   = City of [[Bydgoszcz]]\n| maint                   =\n| length                  =\n| length_m                = 6700\n| length_ft               =\n| length_km               =\n| length_mi               =\n| length_ref              = -Google maps\n| length_notes            = \n| width                   = ca. 20m\n| area                    = Downtown ({{lang-pl|\u015ar\u00f3dmie\u015bcie}}), Okole, [[Osowa G\u00f3ra (Bydgoszcz district)|Osowa G\u00f3ra]] districts\n| steps                   =\n| postal_code             =\n| addresses               =\n| location                = [[Bydgoszcz]]\n| construction_start_date = Early 1850s<ref name=\"cinq cinq\">{{cite book| last=|first= |date=1855 |title=Allgemeiner Wohnungs-Anzeiger fur Bromberg 1855 |location=Bromberg |publisher=Verlag von M. Aronsohn's Buchhandlung |pages=50}}</ref>\n| completion_date         = \n| demolition_date         =\n| north                   =\n| east                    =\n| south                   =\n| west                    =\n| designer                =\n| known_for               =\n| status                  =\n}}\n\n'''Grunwaldzka street''', laid in the [[1850s]], is an extended axis in [[Bydgoszcz]], [[Poland]]. Many frontages on this street offer architectural interests: some of the buildings are registered on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List'''.\n\n==Location==\nThe street runs on an west north-west axis, leading to [[Nak\u0142o nad Noteci\u0105]] (towards [[Pi\u0142a]] and [[Szczecin]]). It connects Bydgoszcz downtown district to western city areas (i.e. Okole, Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko, [[Flisy (Bydgoszcz district)|Flisy]], [[Osowa G\u00f3ra (Bydgoszcz district)|Osowa G\u00f3ra]]). [[National roads in Poland|Polish national road No. 80]] runs along the street located north of [[Bydgoszcz Canal]] and Polish national road No. 25 south of the canal. It is one of the longest and busiest axis of Bydgoszcz.\n\n==History==\n'''Grunwaldzka street''' is mentioned on a 1855 address book of [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]]<ref name=\"cinq cinq\"/>, but appears as early as 1827 as a path to Nak\u0142o nad Noteci\u0105.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gordon |first=Wincenty |date=1974 |title=Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |pages=89-92}}</ref> On a 1857 map, then on a 1876 city map the axis is mentioned as a ''Berliner Chaussee''<ref>1876 Plan der Stadt Bromberg</ref> or ''Highway to [[Berlin]]''. At that time, it appears as an extension of the ''Berliner Stra\u00dfe'' (today's [[Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street in Bydgoszcz|Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street]]) to the west. In 1851, the railway from [[Berlin]] to [[Kaliningrad]] -via Bromberg- is built along that path. \n[[File:1876 STADT BROMBERG Berliner str Berliner chaussee.jpg|thumb|centre|Berliner strasse (black) and Berliner Chaussee (red) on a 1876 map]]\n\nIn 1895, a [[narrow-gauge railway]] from Bydgoszcz to [[Koronowo]] was laid, with a station on Grunwaldzka street, ''Bydgoszcz W\u0105skotorowa'', linked to the city [[Streetcar|tram]] network in 1898. The railway did not survive [[WWII]] and is now operated for touristic purposes between two villages west of Nak\u0142o: railtracks on Grunwaldzka were pulled part in 1969. The tramway line in the street has been dismantled in 1984.<ref name=\"DW\">{{cite book |last=D\u0119bicki |first=Witold |date=1996|title=CzyKomunikacja miejska. Bydgoska gospodarka komunalna\u017ck\u00f3wko |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Bydgoszcz: Instytut Wydawniczy \u201e\u015awiadectwo\u201d |isbn=83-85860-37-1 |page=}}</ref> \n\nBecause of its exceptional length, the avenue, originating from [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]], crossed several other suburban villages which eventually ([[1960s]]) were incorporated into Bydgoszcz territory.<ref>{{cite book |last=Licznerski|first=Alfons |date=1971 |title=ROZWOJ TERYTORIALNY BYDGOSZCZY|location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy. 1964-1965 |pages=7-16}}</ref> As a consequence, the street in its whole bore many different names associated with conflicting [[house numbering]].\n\nIn 2019-2020, municipal authorities have launched an extensive rebuilt of the avenue, so as to enlarge it to a dual carriageway with two lanes along most of its length.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/56,48722,24396740,rozbudowa-ulicy-grunwaldzkiej-2020-rok-koszt-ok-113-mln-zl,,4.html |title=Rozbudowa ulicy Grunwaldzkiej. 2020 rok. Koszt - ok. 113 mln z\u0142 |last=Leszczy\u0144ska |first=Marta |date=25 January 2019 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are two railway viaducts along the street:\n* the first on the way out of the city center dates back to the 1970s and ease the crossing by Bydgoszcz - [[Pi\u0142a]] railway line;\n* the second supports the railway lines from Bydgoszcz to [[Inowroc\u0142aw]] was completed in 2014 to replace the initial bridge from 1872.<ref name=\"DW\"/>\n\nThrough history, this street bore the following names:<ref>{{cite book |last=Czachorowski |first=Antoni |date=1997 |title=Atlas historyczny miast polskich, Tom II Kujawy. Zeszyt I Bydgoszcz |url= |location=Toru\u0144  |publisher= Uniwersytet Miko\u0142aja Kopernika |page= |isbn=}}</ref>\n* From inception in the [[1850]]s to 1902, \n** ''Berliner stra\u00dfe'' and ''Berliner chausseee'' (Bydgoszcz territory);\n** ''Linden stra\u00dfe'' (Schleusenau area);\n** ''Chausse stra\u00dfe'' (Okolo area).\n* 1903-1920, \n** ''Berliner stra\u00dfe'' on Bydgoszcz soil;\n** ''Chaussee Stra\u00dfe (nach Nakel)'' (''Route to [[Nak\u0142o nad Noteci\u0105|Nachel]]'') on Schleusenau area.\n* 1920-1939, ''Ulica Grunwaldzka'';\n* 1939-1945, ''Berliner stra\u00dfe'';\n* Since 1945, ''Ulica Grunwaldzka''.\n\nCurrent name refers to the [[Battle of Grunwald]] (July 15, 1410), part of the [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian\u2013Teutonic War]], where the alliance of the [[Crown of the Kingdom of Poland|Kingdom of Poland]] and the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]], decisively defeated [[Teutonic Knights]], led by Grand Master [[Ulrich von Jungingen]].\n\n== Main areas and edifices ==\nGrunwaldzka stems out of a large city roundabout ({{lang-pl|Rondo Grunwaldzkie}}) where it connects with [[Marshal Ferdinand Foch Street in Bydgoszcz|Focha]], [[Nakielska street in Bydgoszcz|Nakielska]] and Kruszwicka streets.\n\n'''Tenement at No. 1/3'''\n\nBuilt in 1910<ref name=\"ZAR\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=7 August 2015 |title=Zarz\u0105dzenie NR439/2015 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Miasto Bydgoszczy |pages=38\u201339}}</ref>, by [[Bydgoszcz_Architects_(1850-1970s)|Theodor Patzwald]] \n\n[[Modern_architecture#Early_modernism_in_Europe_(1900\u20131914)|Early modernism]]\n\nThe first owners of the tenement were the Goltz brothers (Gustaw, Rudolf and Oskar) who, as construction managers, conducted many projects in the city.\nIn July 1912, a restaurant and a cafe -''Parkhaus''- were arranged, with an area as a summer garden: at that time, the place was giving onto the [[Bydgoszcz Canal]]<ref name=\"okole\">{{cite book |last=Daria Br\u0119czewska-Kulesza, Bogna Derkowska-Kostkowska |first=Agnieszka Wysocka, Krzysztof Bartowski, Piotr Winter |date=2004 |title=Bydgoszcz w strone Okola |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Urz\u0105d Miasta Bydgoszczy-Rada Osiedla Okola. Zak\u0142ad Poligraficzny KORDRUK |isbn=83-921725-0-7 |pages=25,27,31,37,39,41,55}}</ref>, which was covered only in the 1970s. The same year, the Goltz brothers sold the ensemble to [[Franke family in Bydgoszcz|C.A. Franke]], a local successful entrepreneur. In that period, the building housed the office of the then [[Mechanical School N\u00b01, Bydgoszcz|Royal School of Arts and Crafts]], as well as the house designer, architect Theodor Patzwald.\n\nLater on, during the [[Second Polish Republic|interwar]], the landlord was August Latte, owner of a cheese warehouse and a factory.<ref name=\"deux six\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1926 |title=Ksi\u0105\u017cka Adresowa Miasta Bydgoszczy : wydana w roku 1926 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=W\u0142adys\u0142aw Weber|chapter=names |pages=175}}</ref> During the recent renovation of the ensemble in 2015, a mural was created on the wall deprived of opening: it displays advertising with old-fashioned deatures from the 1920s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bryla.pl/bryla/1,85301,18037379,Retro_murale_w_Bydgoszczy.html |title=Retro murale w Bydgoszczy |last=red |first= |date=2 June 2015 |website=bryla.pl |publisher=pressland|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe early modernist style still keeps influence from [[Art Nouveau]]: curved [[bow window]]s, a broken segmental [[pediment]], a vegetal [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] and two grand [[loggia]]s adorned with slender [[column]]s and [[wrought iron]] [[grillwork]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 1 1900.jpg|View ca 1900\nFile:Grunwaldzka 1 3.jpg|View of the ensemble at 1/3\nFile:Grunwaldzka 1 retro ad.jpg|Old-fashion style advert mural\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 2'''\n\n1880s<ref name=\"huit zero\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1880 |title=Wohnungs-Anzeiger nebst Adress- und Gesch\u00e4fts-Handbuch f\u00fcr Bromberg und Umgebung : auf das Jahr 1880 |location=Bromberg |publisher=Mittlersche Buchhandlung (A. Fromm Nachf.)|chapter= |pages=IX,XXXI,18,44}}</ref>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nEarly in the 1880s, a restaurant was run there by Reinhard Zindler.<ref name=\"huit zero\"/> In the 1920s, another restaurant stood there, with a cafe, called ''Dom Parkowy'', run by Teodor Sikorski.<ref name=\"deux six\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 2 1915.jpg|Post card from 1915 related to Sikorski's restaurant\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 6'''\n\n1906<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\nLate [[Art Nouveau]]\n\nThe initial adress of the building was ''19 Berliner Stra\u00dfe''. First register landlord was Gustav Templin, a tradesman.<ref name=\"zero un\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1901 |title=Adressbuch nebst allgemeinem Gesch\u00e4fts-Anzeiger von Bromberg und dessen Vororten auf das Jahr 1901 : auf Grund amtlicher und privater Unterlagen |location=Bromberg |publisher=Dittmann|chapter=names |pages=184,199}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the frontage lost its architectural decoration, one can still appreciate the large [[Cant (architecture)|canted]] [[bay window]] overlooking the entrance, with a floral [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] at its base.<ref name=\"okole\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 6.jpg|Facade onto the street\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 14'''\n\n1900s<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\nLate [[Art Nouveau]]\n\nLocated at first at ''17 Berliner Stra\u00dfe'', the landlord at its construction was Stanislaus Bonneberger, a shoemaker.<ref name=\"neuf cinq\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1895 |title=Adressbuch nebst allgemeinem Gesch\u00e4fts-Anzeiger von Bromberg und dessen Vororten auf das Jahr 1895 : auf Grund amtlicher und privater Unterlagen |location=Bromberg |publisher=Dittmann|chapter=names |pages=19,31,190}}</ref>\n\nThe frontage has lost many of its architectural details, but still exhibits late [[Art Nouveau]] style mixed with modernist influences. Noticeable are the [[wrought iron]] [[balcony|balconies]], a few adorned [[cartouche (design)|cartouche]]s and the decorated entrance [[lintel]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 14.jpg|Building at Grunwaldzka 14\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n''' ''Starofarny Cemetery'' at No. 15'''\n\nIn December 1808, the city hall of [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]] bought 1 [[Hectare|ha]] of land next to the road leading to Szyszk\u00f3wka (today's Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko disctrict), to establish a catholic cemetery: first burials were only performed in 1811, when Prussian authorities banned burying the dead in church cemeteries.<ref name=\"MAJ\">{{cite book |last=Markiewicz  |first=Alojzy Janusz |date=1992 |title=Nie\u015bmiertelne nie umiera! Z dziej\u00f3w Cmentarza Starofarnego w Bydgoszczy |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-Pomorskie Tow. Kulturalne |page=}}</ref>\n''Starofarny Cemetery'' was the first catholic cemetery in the city for which the access road (today's Grunwaldzka street) was cobbled in 1828. In 1855, the cemetery was enlarged by 0.40 ha through purchasing an abuting plot; with several other acquisitions the burial ground reached an area of \u200b\u200b1,425 ha.<ref name=\"GP\">{{cite book |last=Grzybowski |first=Przemys\u0142aw |date=1993 |title=Cmentarz Starofarny i jego rola w \u015bwietle historii pozosta\u0142ych cmentarzy bydgoskich.  Kronika Bydgoska XIII |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |page=}}</ref> The area entered the city limits in 1877, when Okolo district merged with Bydgoszcz territory.\nDuring the second half of the 19th century, the cemetery was embellished: in 1886, a new stone fencing was erected and in 1892, tree avenues were created with [[chestnut]]s, [[maple]]s and [[Tilia|lime trees]]. \nSince Prussian authorities did not allow the creation of additional catholic parishes during the end of the 19th century, ''Starofarny cemetery'' soon got packed: in 1906, eventually, a new parish cemetery was established in the northern suburb of the city, called ''Cmentarz Nowofarny'' ({{lang-en|New parish cemetery}}), to distinguish it from the ''Cmentarz Starofarny'' ({{lang-en|Old parish cemetery}}).\n\nDuring the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|Nazi occupation]], ''Starofarny cemetery'' was repeatedly damaged so as to wipe out Polish traces within the city. Following an order from occupying authorities to remove Polish inscriptions from the tombstones, [[Hitler Youth]] militias destroyed Polish tombstones, beating inscriptions and damaging the fence. In particular, on a Sunday of April 1942, [[Sturmabteilung|SA]] and [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] troops stormed the cemetery, smearing Polish gravestones with cement and destroying metal elements of the graves<ref name=\"GP\"/>.\n\nBetween 1945 and 1964, burials were carried out anew in family graves and in neglected places from the 19th century, which were no more tended. Finally, the last burial took place on July 11, 1964. The cemetery was then declared closed on July 15, 1964, by Bydgoszcz authorities and renamed ''Municipal cemetery''.\nIn the late 1970s, urbanization plans regarding the area where [[Marshal Ferdinand Foch Street in Bydgoszcz|Focha]], Kruszwicka, [[Nakielska street in Bydgoszcz|Nakielska]] and Grunwaldzka streets meet imposed to bulldoze a northern strip of the cemetery. Work started in 1978: it included reconstructing the fence, razing chapels and exhumating some graves. The operation was badly carried out and several errors led to the destruction of a 17th century chapel, the lost of many [[Crypt#Burial_vaults|family crypts]] -some of them being work of art edifices- and the demolition of the caretaker's house. The [[wrought iron]] grating elements of the main entry gate were returned to the [[Poor Clares' Church, Bydgoszcz|church of the Poor Clares]] where it originated from.\n\nThose misbehaviours triggered the establishment of a ''Social Committee for the Rescue of Starofarny Cemetery Monuments'', headed by architect Stefan Klajbor, which succeeded in listing the cemetery on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (No.601242 A/879, June 28, 1983).<ref name=\"class\">zabytek-kujawsko-pomorskie-data dost\u0119pu=28.02.2014</ref> In 1985, [[List of Catholic dioceses in Poland|Metropolitan Curia]] in [[Gniezno]] handed over the management of ''Starofarny Cmentarz'' to Bydgoszcz administrative authorities.<ref name=\"MAJ\"/>\nIn 1991, a restoration plan of the facility was launched, comprising, among others:\n* a reconstruction of the fence;\n* tending the corner of [[Franco-Prussian War|1870 French soldier]] tombs; \n* rebuilding the 17th century chapel. \nSince 1998, the work has been supported by private funds collected locally during [[All Saints' Day]]. \nIn 2018, further contributions also made possible additional renovations such as fencing and family chapels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/5,48722,24118736.html |title=Sikorski i Bruski z puszkami. VIP-y kwestuj\u0105 na renowacj\u0119 cmentarzy |last=Antczak |first=\u0141ukasz |date=1 November 2018 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn 1994, city authorities reopened the cemetery for burials, especially for local distinguished people.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg CmStarofarny 1 07-2013.jpg|Fence \nFile:Brama wej\u015bciowa na cmentarz Starofarny.jpg|Main entry gate onto Grunwaldzka street\nFile:Bydgoski Cmentarz Staro Farny powsta\u0142y w 1806 r - panoramio (3).jpg|Tomb monument\nFile:Bydgoszcz - Cmentarz Staro Farny powsta\u0142 w 1806 r - panoramio.jpg|General view\nFile:Bydgoszcz, cmentarz rzym.-kat. par. (starofarny), 1809c.JPG|Family chapels\nFile:Cmentarz Starofarny 5.jpg|Tomb statue\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 20/22/24'''\n\nBeginning 20th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\nEarly [[Modern architecture]]\n\nThe three buildings date back to the same period, transitioning from fading [[Art Nouveau]] to canted forms of early modernism. This shift appears differently on each of them. While the elevation in the middle (No. 22) is bare of any decoration, its neighbours still display some elements of the late 19th  century style: \n* [[wrought iron]] volutes in the car passageway, adorned [[portal (architecture)|portal]] and oeil-de-boeuf for No. 20;\n* semicircular [[Transom (architecture)|transom]] for No. 24.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 16-26 Bydg 2008f.jpg|View of the frontages from the street\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 26, corner with Graniczna street'''\n\nLate 1890s<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nLocated at the time as the last edifice within [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]] city limits on the avenue, its first landlord was Thomas Diete, who established there a tavern ''To the Golden Star'' ({{lang-ger|Gasthof Zum Goldener Stern}}).<ref name=\"neuf cinq\"/>\n\nThe decoration of the late 19th century have been lost today. Few elements (pediments) remain from the eclectic architectural details, as one can see from early pictures. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 26 1900.jpg|Building and tavern at Grunwaldzka 26 ca 1900\nFile:Grunwaldzka 26.jpg|Building at 26 Grunwaldzka after renovation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Plot at No. 30/32, ex ''BELMA'' Factory'''\n\n1875-1899\n\nIn 1868, Carl Fiebrandt, a journeyman, founded a small mechanical at workshop 11 [[Dworcowa Street]] producing and repairing agricultural machinery. Looking for a place to expand his industry, he bought in 1875, a plot in Okole suburb, at the intersection of Schaussestrasse and Granzstrasse (today's Grunwaldzka and Graniczna streets) and built there a large one-story hall. He quickly realized that the rapid expansion of railways could be a bonanza for him. Hence in 1892, he dedicated exclusively the production to signaling and train traffic control devices.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pomorska.pl/belma-140-lat-tradycji/ar/c3-7004103 |title= Belma - 140 lat tradycji |last=Zielazna |first=Jolanta |date=23 October 2008 |website=pomorska.pl |publisher=Gazeta Pomorska |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1899, Fiebrandt established the ''C. Fiebrandt & Co''-''Eisenbahn-Signalbau-Anstalt Gesellschaft'' ({{lang-en| Railway signal building company}}).\n\nAfter [[WWII]], the firm was taken over by the state treasury and get its name changed first to ''Bydgoska Fabryka Sygna\u0142\u00f3w Kolejowych'' ({{lang-en|Bydgoszcz Railway Signal Factory-State Enterprise}}), then in 1958 to ''Bydgoskie Zak\u0142ady Elektromechaniczne'' ({{lang-en|Bydgoszcz Electro-Mechanical Works}}) or ''[[BELMA]]''. In 1951, the factory started to produce for [[Polish People's Army|army]]: it is now its business staple.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belma.pl/historia |title=Historia |last= |first=|date=2020 |website=belma.pl |publisher=Bydgoskie Zak\u0142ady Elektromechaniczne |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn 2018, the firm celebrated its 150th anniversary from its production site located in the vicinity of Bydgoszcz, at [[Bia\u0142e B\u0142ota, Bydgoszcz County|Bia\u0142e B\u0142ota]].\n\nToday are still visible the [[wrought iron]] grate of the main gate, flanked by two front buildings onto Grunwaldzka street at Nos 30 and 32.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 32 34 Belma 1890s.jpg|Picture of the site in the 1890s\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 34'''\n\nEarly 1880s<ref name=\"huit zero\"/>\n\n[[Renaissance Revival architecture|Neo-Renaissance]], elements of [[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo-Baroque]]\n\nThe edifice was initially located on Okole village land, under the adress ''5 Chaussee Stra\u00dfe'': the landlord was Ludwik D\u00fcrr, a butcher. His son Ernst took over the business and ran it till the late 1920s. A butcher shop has been operated there till the outbreak of [[WWII]].<ref name=\"trois trois\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1933 |title=Ksi\u0105\u017cka Adresowa Miasta Bydgoszczy : na rok 1933 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=W\u0142adys\u0142aw Weber|chapter=|pages=29}}</ref>\n\nThe elevation is rendered unbalanced by the heavy [[bossage]]d [[bay window]] featuring a [[loggia]]. The left side shows adorned windows with [[festoon]]s in cartouches, [[pilaster]]s, curved [[pediment]]s bearing a stylized [[coat of arms]] and a top [[corbel]] table.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 34.jpg|Facade at 34 Grunwaldzka\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 7 07-2013.jpg|Detail of the pediment\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 35'''\n\n1850-1900<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nSituated in Schleusenau suburb, at ''9 Lindenstra\u00dfe'', it was the property of a carpenter, Heinrich G\u00fcrich.<ref name=\"neuf zero\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1890 |title=Adressbuch nebst allgemeinem Gesch\u00e4fts-Anzeiger von Bromberg und dessen Vororten auf das Jahr 1890: auf Grund amtlicher und privater Unterlagen |location=Bromberg |publisher=Dittmann|chapter=names |pages=66,82,159}}</ref> In the 1910s, the ground floor housed a plumber store ran by Friedrich Kolbe (see gallery) at ''107 Chaussee stra\u00dfe''.\n\nThe balanced facade has been renovated in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bydgoszczwbudowie.blogspot.com/2017/09/remonty-kamienic-wrzesien-2017.html |title=Remonty kamienic Wrzesie\u0144 2017 |last=|first=|date=September 2017 |website=bydgoszczwbudowie.blogspot.com |publisher=bydgoszczwbudowie |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 35 1910 1914.jpg|F. Kolbe shop in the 1910s\nFile:Grunwaldzka 35.jpg|Renovated elevation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Pharmacy ''Under the lion'' at No. 37'''\n\n1894<ref name=\"okole\"/>, by [[J\u00f3zef \u015awi\u0119cicki]] and [[Bydgoszcz_Architects_(1850-1970s)#Karl_Bergner|Karl Bergner]]\n\n[[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo Baroque]], [[Rococo]] and [[Mannerism#Mannerist_architecture|Mannerism]]\n\nDr Leonhard Tonn began to run a pharmacy at this spot before commissionning the house. He contracted architect J\u00f3zef Swiecicki who worked with Karl Bergner; builder was well-known entrepreneur [[Bydgoszcz_Architects_(1850-1970s)#Carl_Rose|Carl Rose]].<ref name=\"okole\"/> In March 1894 Dr. Tonn established the ''L\u00f6wen Apotheke Laboratorium f\u00fcr chemische und mikroskopische Untersuchungen - Dr. L. Tonn'' ({{lang-en|Under the lion-Pharmacy laboratory for chemical and microscopic analysis}}). On October 15, 1924, while Bydgoszcz ahd reintegrated [[History of Poland (1918\u20131939)|Polish territory]], the shop was sold to Piotr and Henryk Umbreit, two brothers from [[Pozna\u0144]]. In 1880, they had already founded in their city a pharmaceutical and chemical warehouse, at that time the second Polish medicine factory in Pozna\u0144.<ref name=\"ZJ\">{{cite web |url=https://pomorska.pl/wielkopolscy-farmaceuci-zostawili-slad-w-bydgoszczy/ar/6983411 |title=Wielkopolscy farmaceuci zostawili \u015blad w Bydgoszczy|last=Zielazna |first=Jolanta |date=30 July 2008 |website=pomorska.pl |publisher=Gazeta pomorska |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> In parallel, a medical cabinet opened in the house: in May 1926, dr. Teofil Kowalski from Warsaw succeded to dr. Keslinger, from [[Gda\u0144sk]].\nDuring the Second World War, the management of the pharmacy was taken over by German chemist Georg Kubisch, a member of [[Sturmabteilung|SA]] from Gda\u0144sk, and the name changed to ''L\u00f6wen Apotheke''. In 1940, the pharmacy receives the name ''Hindenburg Apotheke'' since it was also used as a training facility for chemistry students. In 1951, the firm was nationalized as ''Social Pharmacy No. 12'', but its original name ''Pod Lwem'' was reinstated in 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last=Czajkowski|first=Edmund |date=1984|title=Apteka \"Pod Lwem\". Kalendarz Bydgoski  |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy | pages=95-97}}</ref>\n\nAt its opening, the pharmacy was equipped with oak furniture imported from [[Berlin]], the bronze lion painted in gold came from Italy.The emblem is one of the few original preserved pharmacy emblems in Poland.<ref name=\"okole\"/> The building boasts a rich decoration dominated by various styles elements ([[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo Baroque]], [[Rococo]] and [[Mannerism#Mannerist_architecture|Mannerism]]). Together with the standing golden lion, the house is characterized by its [[onion dome]] bearing a [[weather vane]] with a lion [[silhouette]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 22 07-2013.jpg|Elevation on the street\nFile:Lion apteka.jpg|Pharmacy emblem\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 37 Bydg 2008 he\u0142m.jpg|Neo Baroque onion dome\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 20 07-2013.jpg|Detail of the weather vane\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 42, corner with Jasna Street'''\n\nEnd of 19th century-1905<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>, by F. Pretzel<ref name=\"okole\"/>\n\n[[Art Nouveau]]\n\nBuilt in Okole suburb at ''7 Chausseestra\u00dfe'', its owner was a merchant, Carl Raddatz.<ref name=\"neuf zero\"/> The Raddatz family kept the property till the outbreak of [[WWII]].<ref name=\"trois trois\"/>\n\nThe building has undergone an overhaul in 2017, underlining the [[stucco]]ed motifs, especially on the [[pediment]]ed wall [[dormer]] giving onto Grunwaldzka street.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 40 42 1908.jpg|The tenement4 in 1908\nFile:Grunwaldzka 42.jpg|View from the street crossing\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 49'''\n\n1885<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nConstructed on Schleusenau ground in the late 1880s, it has been commissionned by Ludwig Wegener, a boatsman.<ref name=\"huit cinq\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1885 |title=Wohnungs-Anzeiger nebst Adress- und Gesch\u00e4fts-Handbuch f\u00fcr Bromberg und Umgebung : auf das Jahr 1885 |location=Bromberg |publisher=Mittlersche Buchhandlung (A. Fromm Nachf.)|chapter=|pages=149}}</ref>\n\nThe building endured a renovation in 2016.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 49.jpg|Facade on Grunwaldzka street\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Building at No. 50'''\n\n1958-1959<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Modern architecture]], [[Neoclassical architecture]]\n\nThis large edifice was commissionned by the firm ''[[BELMA]]'' settled at No. 30/32. It was designed as a cultural and educational center ({{lang-pl|Dom Kultury}}) for the benefit of ''BELMA'' employees and later also for students from nearby schools. During holidays in particular, the institution used to organize puppet theater performances and film screenings.<ref name=\"okole\"/> \nToday the edifice houses the [[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship|Kuyavian-Pomeranian]] Tax Office in Bydgoszcz.\n\nThe facility has a large auditorium with a stage. It is an architectural example of [[Stalinist_architecture#Poland|Socialist realist construction]].\nIn Bydgoszcz, it is the second largest public facility built after 1950, after the [[Pomeranian Philharmonic]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 14 07-2013.jpg|View of the facade on Grunwaldzka street\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka K-PUS Bydg 2008a.jpg|Detail of the [[portal (architecture)|portal]] with [[column]]s\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 53'''{{break}}\nRegistered on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (A/1681 July, 24, 2015).<ref name=\"class\"/>\n\n1890<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nEduard Schulz, the house investor, was a secretary of the railway. The property remained in the hands of the Schulz family during the interwar period.<ref name=\"okole\"/> \n\nOn the facade boasts a collection of ornamentation:\n* a main entrance flanked by [[Corinthian order|corinthian]] style columns;\n* a [[bossage]] wall on the ground floor;\n* the first [[belt course]] supports [[pilaster]]s and a [[column]]ed [[loggia]] with a round [[architrave]];\n* the second string course carries two series of round top [[mullion]]ed windows separated by an [[oeil-de-boeuf]];\n* a large [[cornice]] tops the frontage. \nThis house has been refurbished in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bydgoszcz.pl/aktualnosci/tresc/dbamy-o-zabytki-elewacja-na-okolu-w-pelnej-krasi/ |title=Dbamy o zabytki. Elewacja na Okolu w pe\u0142nej krasie |last=|first=|date=8 January 2020 |website=bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=Miasto Bydgoszcz |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 53 1907.jpg|53 Grunwaldzka on a postcard ca 1907\nFile:Bdg Grunwaldzka53 2 02-2014.jpg|Building before renovation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Building at No. 55'''\n\n1890<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Art Nouveau]]\n\nThe commissionner of this building was Marie Jacobowski, owner of tenements at No. 57 and 59, where she lived.<ref name=\"neuf zero\"/> After a heavy fire damage in 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz998.wordpress.com/2012/12/28/grozny-pozar-mieszkania-przy-ulicy-grunwaldzkiej-55-w-bydgoszczy/ |title=Gro\u017any po\u017car mieszkania przy ulicy Grunwaldzkiej 55 w Bydgoszczy |last=\u017bywoci\u0144ski |first=Artur |date=28 December 2012 |website=bydgoszcz 998 |publisher=bydgoszcz998.wordpress |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> the municpal authorities have decided in 2019 to sell the property to private hands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.naszemiasto.pl/zamiast-pustych-slow-maja-byc-puste-lokale-radny-zrobil/ar/c1-7335829 |title=Zamiast pustych s\u0142\u00f3w maj\u0105 by\u0107 puste lokale. Radny zrobi\u0142 list\u0119 |last=Stasiewicz |first=Anna |date=13 September 2019 |website=bydgoszcz.naszemiasto.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.naszemiasto |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough damaged, the main elevation offers to the viewer topping [[loggia]]s crowned by a [[festoon]], a [[bay window]] with geometrical motifs and an adorned [[portal (architecture)|portal]]. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 53-55 Bydg 2008.jpg|View of elevations at 53 and 55\nFile:Grunwaldzka 55.jpg|Frontage onto the street\nFile:Grunwaldzka 55 portal.jpg|Detail of the portal at 55 Grunwaldzka\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 57/59, corner with Kana\u0142owa street'''\n\nEnd 19th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nBoth buildings (along with No. 55) were the property of Marie Jacobowski, who lived at 59.<ref name=\"neuf zero\"/> Between the early 1900s and the end of the [[Second Polish Republic|interwar]] period, the ground floor at 57 housed a tobacco shop.<ref name=\"trois trois\"/>\n\nFacades did not keep the architectural richness: still noticeable are the corner [[wrought iron]] [[balcony|balconies]] facing each other across Kana\u0142owa street. The tenement at 57 has been refurbished in 2017-2018. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 57 59 1914.jpg|No. 57 59 on a 1914 postcard\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 53-57 Bydg 2008b.jpg|Building at 57 (far right) before renovation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 72/74 and 78'''\n\nEnd 19th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nWhile No. 72 and 74 had private owners, the tenement at 78 was initially the property of the [[Prussian Eastern Railway]], as its location commanded a view on the line from [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]] to [[Kaliningrad]]. After 1920 and the [[History_of_Poland#Second_Polish_Republic_(1918\u20131939)|restoration of the Polish state]], the house was taken over by the ''Bydgoszcz Railway'' ({{lang-pl|Bydgoskie Koleje Powiatowe}}), the local disctrict of the [[Polish State Railways]] ({{lang-pl| Polskie Koleje Pa\u0144stwowe}}).<ref name=\"trois trois\"/> \n\nAll three houses are in a neglected state and few details still prevail, apart from the decoration around the windows ([[pediment]]s, garnished [[lintel]] and cartouches). \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 72 74.jpg|Buildings at 72 74 \nFile:Grunwaldzka 78.jpg|Building at 78 \n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 98'''\n\nEarly 20th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Art Nouveau]]\n\nThe commissionner was Heinrich Seellen.<ref name=\"zero un\"/>\n\nThe building has been deeply refurbished in 2019, after a sell by the municipal authorities to a private company.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bydgoszcz.pl/aktualnosci/tresc/odnowiona-kamienica-zdobi-ulice-grunwaldzka/ |title=Odnowiona kamienica zdobi ulic\u0119 Grunwaldzk\u0105 |last=|first=|date=15 January 2019 |website=bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=Miasto Bydgoszcz |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The thorough renovation highlights\n[[Art Nouveau]] motifs, such as the [[stucco]]ed patterns on the top of each wall [[gable]] crowing the two [[terraced house|terraces]]. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 98.jpg|98 Grunwaldzka before restoration\nFile:Grunwaldzka 98 2.jpg|98 Grunwaldzka refurbished\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 102 to 118'''\n\nEarly 20th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Modern_architecture]]\n\nThe ensemble was owned by the [[Prussian Eastern Railway]] ({{lang-de|Preu\u00dfische Ostbahn}}) and built in three stages: 1904 (houses 108 to 114), then 1911 (102 and 104) and 1912 (116-118). The railway company housed here its employees, mostly drivers and auxiliary staff, together with some low-level officials. Up to 50 families used to be accommodated in this housing blocks.<ref name=\"okole\"/>\n\nA modern project of residence is planned to be squeezed at 106 (only free plot) in 2020.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg ul Grunwaldzka 4 5-2015.jpg|Housing ensemble along the street\nFile:Bdg ul Grunwaldzka 2 5-2015.jpg|One of the houses\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Catholic church Saint [[Anthony of Padua]], crossing with Koronowska street'''\n\nRegistered on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (No.690851 A/1159 August 3, 2006).<ref name=\"class\"/>\n\n1936-1945<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Modern architecture]]\n\nAt the time of the re-creation of the Polish state, the area was part of the ''Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko'' village, which will be combined with Bydgoszcz territory in the late 1920s. The new district was subordinated to the downtown [[Church of the Holy Trinity in Bydgoszcz|parish of the Holy Trinity]], several kilometers away. In this situation, a dance hall was purchased in 1923 to be replaced by a chapel, [[consecration|consecrated]] on February 24, 1924.<ref name=\"padova\">{{cite book |last=Wysocka |first=Agnieszka|date=2008 |title=Ko\u015bcio\u0142y projektu Stefana Cybichowskiego w Bydgoszczy i okolicach miasta. Kronika Bydgoska XXX |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy| pages= |language=pl}}</ref>\n\nA request to create a new parish in this area was granted by [[Primate (bishop)|bishop]] [[August Hlond]] and the parish was inaugurated on July 1, 1933, dedicated to [[Anthony of Padua]], hence endorsing the separation from the Holy Trinity church. The construction of the church, funded partly by [[Antoni Laubitz]], the bishop of [[Gniezno]], began in 1936: the design was realized a year earlier by [[Pozna\u0144]] architect Stefan Cybichowski.<ref name=\"padova\"/> The edifice was not completed at the start of [[WWII]] and had been used by Nazi forces as a warehouse for construction tools, while religious services were held back in the initial chapel.\nAfter the war, the church was left devastated and shelled, but after a hasty renovation, it had been consecrated anew by bishop [[August Hlond]] on December 1, 1945.<ref name=\"padova\"/>\n\nThe massive brick church has three [[nave]]s, with a semi-circular northern [[chancel]]. The highlight of the building is the high square [[steeple]], visible from Grunwaldzka street crossing. Inside, several [[stained glass]]es cover the openings. \nThe central nave is separated by [[pillar]]s with decorative goblets [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]] supporting a [[Barrel vault|vaulted roof]].<ref name=\"padova\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:38. kosciol padewskiego bydgoszcz.JPG|View from the church parvis\nFile:Bydgoszcz Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw Antoniego 2.jpg|External view of the chancel\nFile:Bydgoszcz Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw Antoniego 1.jpg|Detail of the steeple, still bearing some 1945 damages\nFile:Kosciol sw Antoniego Padewskiego Consecration 1945.jpg|Leaflet for the 1945 consecration\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Catholic church Saint [[Maximilian Kolbe]], corner with Kolibrowa street'''\n\n1982-1991\n\n[[Modern architecture]]\n\nGrunwaldzka street cuts through a patch of forest before entering another urban area where stands the church.\nA pastoral center has been active in this area since in 1970. One of its member, Jadwiga Wo\u015b, donated a swathe of her land to have a chapel built. A first service was celebrated there on March 9, 1972, for the ten following years. The parish ''St. Maximilian Kolbe'' was erected on July 1, 1981.<ref name=\"hist paraf\">{{cite web |url=http://mkolbe.bydgoszcz.pl/o-parafii/historia-parafii/ |title=Historia parafii |last=|first=|date=2017 |website=mkolbe.bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=Parafia pw. \u015bw. Maksymiliana Kolbego |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> \nThe cornerstone of the church (coming from an ancient roman temple on Lech Hill in Gniezno) was laid on May 25, 1983 in a ceremony attended among others by the Primate of Poland, [[J\u00f3zef Glemp]]. On May 26, 1991, Cardinal J\u00f3zef Glemp solemnly consecrated the new church in the [[Osowa G\u00f3ra (Bydgoszcz district)|Osowa G\u00f3ra district]].\n\nThe church is built in a modern style. On the main wall of the chancel one can admire a 7-m-high bronze [[bas-relief]] of the Parish [[Patron saint]]. The architectural structure also comprises [[catechesis|catechetical]] rooms, a parish office and a daily chapel.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bird eye forest.jpg|Grunwaldzka street through the forest before reaching the church\nFile:Bydgoszcz Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw Maksymiliana Kolbe 2.jpg|View of the church from the street \nFile:Osowa G\u00f3ra Parafia rzymskokatolicka pw.\u015bw Maksymiliana Kolbego - panoramio.jpg|Northern view\nFile:OsowaGora ParafiaA 2.JPG|The chancel with the bas-relief \n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Restaurant ''Karczma Rzym'' '''\n\nThe last estate on Grunwaldzka street prior to leaving Bydgoszcz territory, is  ''Karczma Rzym'' ({{lang-en|[[Rome]] Inn}}), a traditional restaurant.\nIt offers traditional Polish cuisine and bears a name widely spread in Poland for such an establishment .\n\n''Karczma Rzym'' alludes to [[Adam Mickiewicz]]'s [[Pan Twardowski]], where a sorcerer (Twardowski) sellshis soul to the devil in exchange for eternal life and special powers. However, Twardowski, willing to ouwit the devil, includes a special clause in the contract, stating that Satan will own Twardowski's soul only if he visits Rome \u2013 a place the sorcerer never intends to go to. The devil's trick relied on luring the sorcerer into a newly built tavern called ''Rome Inn''.\n\nLegend has it that Pan Twardowski spent some time in [[Bydgoszcz]], where, as a celebration as well as a touristic attraction, a figure was recently mounted in a window of a tenement, overseeing the [[Old Market square, Bydgoszcz|Old Market square]]. Every day at 13:13 and 21:13, third storey window at No.15 opens and Pan Twardowski appears, accompanied by music and a devilish laughter. He takes a bow, waves his hand, and then disappears, to the delight of gathered spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://visitbydgoszcz.pl/en/explore/what-to-see/2568-master-twardowski |title=MASTER TWARDOWSKI |last=|first=|date=2018 |website=visitbydgoszcz.pl |publisher=visitbydgoszcz |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Karczma Rzym.jpg|Restaurant Karczma Rzym\nFile:Pan Twardowski 09 2009.jpg|Pan Twardowski statue in Bydgoszcz\nFile:Stary Rynek Bydg Twardowski.jpg|No.15 on Old Market Place\n</gallery>\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Grunwaldzka Street in Bydgoszcz}}\n* [[Bydgoszcz]]\n* [[Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street in Bydgoszcz|Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street]]\n* [[BELMA]]\n* [[Pan Twardowski]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Br\u0119czewska-Kulesza|first=Daria|date=2004 |title=Przegl\u0105d styl\u00f3w wyst\u0119puj\u0105cych w bydgoskiej architekturze drugiej po\u0142owy XIX i pocz\u0105tku XX stulecia. Bydgoszcz w stron\u0119 Okola |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Zesp\u00f3\u0142 Pracowni Dokumentacji i Popularyzacji Zabytk\u00f3w Wojew\u00f3dzkiego O\u015brodka Kultury w Bydgoszczy| pages=| ISBN=83-921725-0-7|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=Czachorowski |first=Antoni |date=1997 |title=Atlas historyczny miast polskich. Tom II Kujawy. Zeszyt I Bydgoszcz. |location=Toru\u0144 |publisher=Uniwersytet Miko\u0142aja Kopernika| pages=| ISBN=|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=Derenda |first=Jerzy |date=2006 |title=Pi\u0119kna stara Bydgoszcz. Tom I z serii: Bydgoszcz miasto na Kujawach |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy| pages=| ISBN=83-916178-0-7|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jastrz\u0119bska-Puzowska|first=Iwona|date=2005 |title=Od miasteczka do metropolii. Rozw\u00f3j architektoniczny i urbanistyczny Bydgoszczy w latach 1850-1920 |location=Toru\u0144 |publisher=Wydawnictwo MADO| pages=| ISBN=83-89886-38-3|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last= |first= |author-link= |date=2004 |title=Bydgoszcz w stron\u0119 Okola. |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Zesp\u00f3\u0142 Pracowni Dokumentacji i Popularyzacji Zabytk\u00f3w Wojew\u00f3dzkiego O\u015brodka Kultury w Bydgoszczy |page= |isbn=83-921725-0-7|language=pl}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cmentarze.bydgoszcz.pl/ ''Starofarny'' Municipal cemetery]\n* [http://www.belma.pl/en/ BELMA company]\n* [https://www.kujawsko-pomorskie.kas.gov.pl/kujawsko-pomorski-urzad-skarbowy-w-bydgoszczy/kontakt/dane-teleadresowe Kuyavian-Pomeranian Tax Office in Bydgoszcz]\n* [https://antonibydgoszcz.pl/ Saint Anthony Parish] \n* [http://mkolbe.bydgoszcz.pl/ Saint Maximilian Kolbe Parish]\n* [https://www.karczmarzym.com.pl/ Restaurant Karczma Rzym]\n\n\n{{coord|53|08|29|N|17|56|29|E|source:wikimapia|display=title}}\n{{Bydgoszcz streets and squares}}\n \n[[:Category:Cultural heritage monuments in Bydgoszcz]]\n[[:Category:Streets and squares in Bydgoszcz]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Grunwaldzka street\n| marker_image            = Bydgoszcz\n| native_name             = {{lang-pl|Ulica Grunwaldzka w Bydgoszczy}}\n| alternate_name          =\n| image                   = File:Ul Grunwaldzka 16-26 Bydg 2008e.jpg\n| image_size              = 250 px\n| image_map               = File:Bydgoszcz ul Grunwaldzka.png\n| caption                 = View of historic facades on Grunwaldzka street\n| map_size                = 250 px\n| map_caption             = Grunwaldzka Street highlighted on a Bydgoszcz map\n| map_alt                 =\n| other_name              = \n| former_names            =  \n| part_of                 = \n| namesake                = [[Battle of Grunwald]]\n| type                    =\n| owner                   = City of [[Bydgoszcz]]\n| maint                   =\n| length                  =\n| length_m                = 6700\n| length_ft               =\n| length_km               =\n| length_mi               =\n| length_ref              = -Google maps\n| length_notes            = \n| width                   = ca. 20m\n| area                    = Downtown ({{lang-pl|\u015ar\u00f3dmie\u015bcie}}), Okole, [[Osowa G\u00f3ra (Bydgoszcz district)|Osowa G\u00f3ra]] districts\n| steps                   =\n| postal_code             =\n| addresses               =\n| location                = [[Bydgoszcz]]\n| construction_start_date = Early 1850s<ref name=\"cinq cinq\">{{cite book| last=|first= |date=1855 |title=Allgemeiner Wohnungs-Anzeiger fur Bromberg 1855 |location=Bromberg |publisher=Verlag von M. Aronsohn's Buchhandlung |pages=50}}</ref>\n| completion_date         = \n| demolition_date         =\n| north                   =\n| east                    =\n| south                   =\n| west                    =\n| designer                =\n| known_for               =\n| status                  =\n}}\n\n'''Grunwaldzka street''', laid in the [[1850s]], is an extended axis in [[Bydgoszcz]], [[Poland]]. Many frontages on this street offer architectural interests: some of the buildings are registered on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List'''.\n\n==Location==\nThe street runs on an west north-west axis, leading to [[Nak\u0142o nad Noteci\u0105]] (towards [[Pi\u0142a]] and [[Szczecin]]). It connects Bydgoszcz downtown district to western city areas (i.e. Okole, Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko, [[Flisy (Bydgoszcz district)|Flisy]], [[Osowa G\u00f3ra (Bydgoszcz district)|Osowa G\u00f3ra]]). [[National roads in Poland|Polish national road No. 80]] runs along the street located north of [[Bydgoszcz Canal]] and Polish national road No. 25 south of the canal. It is one of the longest and busiest axis of Bydgoszcz.\n\n==History==\n'''Grunwaldzka street''' is mentioned on a 1855 address book of [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]]<ref name=\"cinq cinq\"/>, but appears as early as 1827 as a path to Nak\u0142o nad Noteci\u0105.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gordon |first=Wincenty |date=1974 |title=Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |pages=89-92}}</ref> On a 1857 map, then on a 1876 city map the axis is mentioned as a ''Berliner Chaussee''<ref>1876 Plan der Stadt Bromberg</ref> or ''Highway to [[Berlin]]''. At that time, it appears as an extension of the ''Berliner Stra\u00dfe'' (today's [[Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street in Bydgoszcz|Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street]]) to the west. In 1851, the railway from [[Berlin]] to [[Kaliningrad]] -via Bromberg- is built along that path. \n[[File:1876 STADT BROMBERG Berliner str Berliner chaussee.jpg|thumb|centre|Berliner strasse (black) and Berliner Chaussee (red) on a 1876 map]]\n\nIn 1895, a [[narrow-gauge railway]] from Bydgoszcz to [[Koronowo]] was laid, with a station on Grunwaldzka street, ''Bydgoszcz W\u0105skotorowa'', linked to the city [[street car|tram]] network in 1898. The railway did not survive [[WWII]] and is now operated for touristic purposes between two villages west of Nak\u0142o: railtracks on Grunwaldzka were pulled part in 1969. The tramway line in the street has been dismantled in 1984.<ref name=\"DW\">{{cite book |last=D\u0119bicki |first=Witold |date=1996|title=CzyKomunikacja miejska. Bydgoska gospodarka komunalna\u017ck\u00f3wko |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Bydgoszcz: Instytut Wydawniczy \u201e\u015awiadectwo\u201d |isbn=83-85860-37-1 |page=}}</ref> \n\nBecause of its exceptional length, the avenue, originating from [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]], crossed several other suburban villages which eventually ([[1960s]]) were incorporated into Bydgoszcz territory.<ref>{{cite book |last=Licznerski|first=Alfons |date=1971 |title=ROZWOJ TERYTORIALNY BYDGOSZCZY|location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy. 1964-1965 |pages=7-16}}</ref> As a consequence, the street in its whole bore many different names associated with conflicting [[house numbering]].\n\nIn 2019-2020, municipal authorities have launched an extensive rebuilt of the avenue, so as to enlarge it to a dual carriageway with two lanes along most of its length.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/56,48722,24396740,rozbudowa-ulicy-grunwaldzkiej-2020-rok-koszt-ok-113-mln-zl,,4.html |title=Rozbudowa ulicy Grunwaldzkiej. 2020 rok. Koszt - ok. 113 mln z\u0142 |last=Leszczy\u0144ska |first=Marta |date=25 January 2019 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are two railway viaducts along the street:\n* the first on the way out of the city center dates back to the 1970s and ease the crossing by Bydgoszcz - [[Pi\u0142a]] railway line;\n* the second supports the railway lines from Bydgoszcz to [[Inowroc\u0142aw]] was completed in 2014 to replace the initial bridge from 1872.<ref name=\"DW\"/>\n\nThrough history, this street bore the following names:<ref>{{cite book |last=Czachorowski |first=Antoni |date=1997 |title=Atlas historyczny miast polskich, Tom II Kujawy. Zeszyt I Bydgoszcz |url= |location=Toru\u0144  |publisher= Uniwersytet Miko\u0142aja Kopernika |page= |isbn=}}</ref>\n* From inception in the [[1850]]s to 1902, \n** ''Berliner stra\u00dfe'' and ''Berliner chausseee'' (Bydgoszcz territory);\n** ''Linden stra\u00dfe'' (Schleusenau area);\n** ''Chausse stra\u00dfe'' (Okolo area).\n* 1903-1920, \n** ''Berliner stra\u00dfe'' on Bydgoszcz soil;\n** ''Chaussee Stra\u00dfe (nach Nakel)'' (''Route to [[Nak\u0142o nad Noteci\u0105|Nachel]]'') on Schleusenau area.\n* 1920-1939, ''Ulica Grunwaldzka'';\n* 1939-1945, ''Berliner stra\u00dfe'';\n* Since 1945, ''Ulica Grunwaldzka''.\n\nCurrent name refers to the [[Battle of Grunwald]] (July 15, 1410), part of the [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian\u2013Teutonic War]], where the alliance of the [[Crown of the Kingdom of Poland|Kingdom of Poland]] and the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]], decisively defeated [[Teutonic Knights]], led by Grand Master [[Ulrich von Jungingen]].\n\n== Main areas and edifices ==\nGrunwaldzka stems out of a large city roundabout ({{lang-pl|Rondo Grunwaldzkie}}) where it connects with [[Marshal Ferdinand Foch Street in Bydgoszcz|Focha]], [[Nakielska street in Bydgoszcz|Nakielska]] and Kruszwicka streets.\n\n'''Tenement at No. 1/3'''\n\nBuilt in 1910<ref name=\"ZAR\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=7 August 2015 |title=Zarz\u0105dzenie NR439/2015 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Miasto Bydgoszczy |pages=38\u201339}}</ref>, by [[Bydgoszcz_Architects_(1850-1970s)|Theodor Patzwald]] \n\n[[Modern_architecture#Early_modernism_in_Europe_(1900\u20131914)|Early modernism]]\n\nThe first owners of the tenement were the Goltz brothers (Gustaw, Rudolf and Oskar) who, as construction managers, conducted many projects in the city.\nIn July 1912, a restaurant and a cafe -''Parkhaus''- were arranged, with an area as a summer garden: at that time, the place was giving onto the [[Bydgoszcz Canal]]<ref name=\"okole\">{{cite book |last=Daria Br\u0119czewska-Kulesza, Bogna Derkowska-Kostkowska |first=Agnieszka Wysocka, Krzysztof Bartowski, Piotr Winter |date=2004 |title=Bydgoszcz w strone Okola |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Urz\u0105d Miasta Bydgoszczy-Rada Osiedla Okola. Zak\u0142ad Poligraficzny KORDRUK |isbn=83-921725-0-7 |pages=25,27,31,37,39,41,55}}</ref>, which was covered only in the 1970s. The same year, the Goltz brothers sold the ensemble to [[Franke family in Bydgoszcz|C.A. Franke]], a local successful entrepreneur. In that period, the building housed the office of the then [[Mechanical School N\u00b01, Bydgoszcz|Royal School of Arts and Crafts]], as well as the house designer, architect Theodor Patzwald.\n\nLater on, during the [[Second Polish Republic|interwar]], the landlord was August Latte, owner of a cheese warehouse and a factory.<ref name=\"deux six\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1926 |title=Ksi\u0105\u017cka Adresowa Miasta Bydgoszczy : wydana w roku 1926 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=W\u0142adys\u0142aw Weber|chapter=names |pages=175}}</ref> During the recent renovation of the ensemble in 2015, a mural was created on the wall deprived of opening: it displays advertising with old-fashioned deatures from the 1920s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bryla.pl/bryla/1,85301,18037379,Retro_murale_w_Bydgoszczy.html |title=Retro murale w Bydgoszczy |last=red |first= |date=2 June 2015 |website=bryla.pl |publisher=pressland|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe early modernist style still keeps influence from [[Art Nouveau]]: curved [[bow window]]s, a broken segmental [[pediment]], a vegetal [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] and two grand [[loggia]]s adorned with slender [[column]]s and [[wrought iron]] [[grillwork]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 1 1900.jpg|View ca 1900\nFile:Grunwaldzka 1 3.jpg|View of the ensemble at 1/3\nFile:Grunwaldzka 1 retro ad.jpg|Old-fashion style advert mural\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 2'''\n\n1880s<ref name=\"huit zero\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1880 |title=Wohnungs-Anzeiger nebst Adress- und Gesch\u00e4fts-Handbuch f\u00fcr Bromberg und Umgebung : auf das Jahr 1880 |location=Bromberg |publisher=Mittlersche Buchhandlung (A. Fromm Nachf.)|chapter= |pages=IX,XXXI,18,44}}</ref>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nEarly in the 1880s, a restaurant was run there by Reinhard Zindler.<ref name=\"huit zero\"/> In the 1920s, another restaurant stood there, with a cafe, called ''Dom Parkowy'', run by Teodor Sikorski.<ref name=\"deux six\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 2 1915.jpg|Post card from 1915 related to Sikorski's restaurant\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 6'''\n\n1906<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\nLate [[Art Nouveau]]\n\nThe initial adress of the building was ''19 Berliner Stra\u00dfe''. First register landlord was Gustav Templin, a tradesman.<ref name=\"zero un\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1901 |title=Adressbuch nebst allgemeinem Gesch\u00e4fts-Anzeiger von Bromberg und dessen Vororten auf das Jahr 1901 : auf Grund amtlicher und privater Unterlagen |location=Bromberg |publisher=Dittmann|chapter=names |pages=184,199}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the frontage lost its architectural decoration, one can still appreciate the large [[Cant (architecture)|canted]] [[bay window]] overlooking the entrance, with a floral [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] at its base.<ref name=\"okole\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 6.jpg|Facade onto the street\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 14'''\n\n1900s<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\nLate [[Art Nouveau]]\n\nLocated at first at ''17 Berliner Stra\u00dfe'', the landlord at its construction was Stanislaus Bonneberger, a shoemaker.<ref name=\"neuf cinq\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1895 |title=Adressbuch nebst allgemeinem Gesch\u00e4fts-Anzeiger von Bromberg und dessen Vororten auf das Jahr 1895 : auf Grund amtlicher und privater Unterlagen |location=Bromberg |publisher=Dittmann|chapter=names |pages=19,31,190}}</ref>\n\nThe frontage has lost many of its architectural details, but still exhibits late [[Art Nouveau]] style mixed with modernist influences. Noticeable are the [[wrought iron]] [[balcony|balconies]], a few adorned [[cartouche (design)|cartouche]]s and the decorated entrance [[lintel]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 14.jpg|Building at Grunwaldzka 14\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n''' ''Starofarny Cemetery'' at No. 15'''\n\nIn December 1808, the city hall of [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]] bought 1 [[Hectare|ha]] of land next to the road leading to Szyszk\u00f3wka (today's Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko disctrict), to establish a catholic cemetery: first burials were only performed in 1811, when Prussian authorities banned burying the dead in church cemeteries.<ref name=\"MAJ\">{{cite book |last=Markiewicz  |first=Alojzy Janusz |date=1992 |title=Nie\u015bmiertelne nie umiera! Z dziej\u00f3w Cmentarza Starofarnego w Bydgoszczy |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-Pomorskie Tow. Kulturalne |page=}}</ref>\n''Starofarny Cemetery'' was the first catholic cemetery in the city for which the access road (today's Grunwaldzka street) was cobbled in 1828. In 1855, the cemetery was enlarged by 0.40 ha through purchasing an abuting plot; with several other acquisitions the burial ground reached an area of \u200b\u200b1,425 ha.<ref name=\"GP\">{{cite book |last=Grzybowski |first=Przemys\u0142aw |date=1993 |title=Cmentarz Starofarny i jego rola w \u015bwietle historii pozosta\u0142ych cmentarzy bydgoskich.  Kronika Bydgoska XIII |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |page=}}</ref> The area entered the city limits in 1877, when Okolo district merged with Bydgoszcz territory.\nDuring the second half of the 19th century, the cemetery was embellished: in 1886, a new stone fencing was erected and in 1892, tree avenues were created with [[chestnut]]s, [[maple]]s and [[Tilia|lime trees]]. \nSince Prussian authorities did not allow the creation of additional catholic parishes during the end of the 19th century, ''Starofarny cemetery'' soon got packed: in 1906, eventually, a new parish cemetery was established in the northern suburb of the city, called ''Cmentarz Nowofarny'' ({{lang-en|New parish cemetery}}), to distinguish it from the ''Cmentarz Starofarny'' ({{lang-en|Old parish cemetery}}).\n\nDuring the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|Nazi occupation]], ''Starofarny cemetery'' was repeatedly damaged so as to wipe out Polish traces within the city. Following an order from occupying authorities to remove Polish inscriptions from the tombstones, [[Hitler Youth]] militias destroyed Polish tombstones, beating inscriptions and damaging the fence. In particular, on a Sunday of April 1942, [[Sturmabteilung|SA]] and [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] troops stormed the cemetery, smearing Polish gravestones with cement and destroying metal elements of the graves<ref name=\"GP\"/>.\n\nBetween 1945 and 1964, burials were carried out anew in family graves and in neglected places from the 19th century, which were no more tended. Finally, the last burial took place on July 11, 1964. The cemetery was then declared closed on July 15, 1964, by Bydgoszcz authorities and renamed ''Municipal cemetery''.\nIn the late 1970s, urbanization plans regarding the area where [[Marshal Ferdinand Foch Street in Bydgoszcz|Focha]], Kruszwicka, [[Nakielska street in Bydgoszcz|Nakielska]] and Grunwaldzka streets meet imposed to bulldoze a northern strip of the cemetery. Work started in 1978: it included reconstructing the fence, razing chapels and exhumating some graves. The operation was badly carried out and several errors led to the destruction of a 17th century chapel, the lost of many [[Crypt#Burial_vaults|family crypts]] -some of them being work of art edifices- and the demolition of the caretaker's house. The [[wrought iron]] grating elements of the main entry gate were returned to the [[Poor Clares' Church, Bydgoszcz|church of the Poor Clares]] where it originated from.\n\nThose misbehaviours triggered the establishment of a ''Social Committee for the Rescue of Starofarny Cemetery Monuments'', headed by architect Stefan Klajbor, which succeeded in listing the cemetery on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (No.601242 A/879, June 28, 1983).<ref name=\"class\">zabytek-kujawsko-pomorskie-data dost\u0119pu=28.02.2014</ref> In 1985, [[List of Catholic dioceses in Poland|Metropolitan Curia]] in [[Gniezno]] handed over the management of ''Starofarny Cmentarz'' to Bydgoszcz administrative authorities.<ref name=\"MAJ\"/>\nIn 1991, a restoration plan of the facility was launched, comprising, among others:\n* a reconstruction of the fence;\n* tending the corner of [[Franco-Prussian War|1870 French soldier]] tombs; \n* rebuilding the 17th century chapel. \nSince 1998, the work has been supported by private funds collected locally during [[All Saints' Day]]. \nIn 2018, further contributions also made possible additional renovations such as fencing and family chapels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/5,48722,24118736.html |title=Sikorski i Bruski z puszkami. VIP-y kwestuj\u0105 na renowacj\u0119 cmentarzy |last=Antczak |first=\u0141ukasz |date=1 November 2018 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn 1994, city authorities reopened the cemetery for burials, especially for local distinguished people.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg CmStarofarny 1 07-2013.jpg|Fence \nFile:Brama wej\u015bciowa na cmentarz Starofarny.jpg|Main entry gate onto Grunwaldzka street\nFile:Bydgoski Cmentarz Staro Farny powsta\u0142y w 1806 r - panoramio (3).jpg|Tomb monument\nFile:Bydgoszcz - Cmentarz Staro Farny powsta\u0142 w 1806 r - panoramio.jpg|General view\nFile:Bydgoszcz, cmentarz rzym.-kat. par. (starofarny), 1809c.JPG|Family chapels\nFile:Cmentarz Starofarny 5.jpg|Tomb statue\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 20/22/24'''\n\nBeginning 20th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\nEarly [[Modern architecture]]\n\nThe three buildings date back to the same period, transitioning from fading [[Art Nouveau]] to canted forms of early modernism. This shift appears differently on each of them. While the elevation in the middle (No. 22) is bare of any decoration, its neighbours still display some elements of the late 19th  century style: \n* [[wrought iron]] volutes in the car passageway, adorned [[portal (architecture)|portal]] and oeil-de-boeuf for No. 20;\n* semicircular [[Transom (architecture)|transom]] for No. 24.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 16-26 Bydg 2008f.jpg|View of the frontages from the street\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 26, corner with Graniczna street'''\n\nLate 1890s<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nLocated at the time as the last edifice within [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]] city limits on the avenue, its first landlord was Thomas Diete, who established there a tavern ''To the Golden Star'' ({{lang-ger|Gasthof Zum Goldener Stern}}).<ref name=\"neuf cinq\"/>\n\nThe decoration of the late 19th century have been lost today. Few elements (pediments) remain from the eclectic architectural details, as one can see from early pictures. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 26 1900.jpg|Building and tavern at Grunwaldzka 26 ca 1900\nFile:Grunwaldzka 26.jpg|Building at 26 Grunwaldzka after renovation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Plot at No. 30/32, ex ''BELMA'' Factory'''\n\n1875-1899\n\nIn 1868, Carl Fiebrandt, a journeyman, founded a small mechanical at workshop 11 [[Dworcowa Street]] producing and repairing agricultural machinery. Looking for a place to expand his industry, he bought in 1875, a plot in Okole suburb, at the intersection of Schaussestrasse and Granzstrasse (today's Grunwaldzka and Graniczna streets) and built there a large one-story hall. He quickly realized that the rapid expansion of railways could be a bonanza for him. Hence in 1892, he dedicated exclusively the production to signaling and train traffic control devices.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pomorska.pl/belma-140-lat-tradycji/ar/c3-7004103 |title= Belma - 140 lat tradycji |last=Zielazna |first=Jolanta |date=23 October 2008 |website=pomorska.pl |publisher=Gazeta Pomorska |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1899, Fiebrandt established the ''C. Fiebrandt & Co''-''Eisenbahn-Signalbau-Anstalt Gesellschaft'' ({{lang-en| Railway signal building company}}).\n\nAfter [[WWII]], the firm was taken over by the state treasury and get its name changed first to ''Bydgoska Fabryka Sygna\u0142\u00f3w Kolejowych'' ({{lang-en|Bydgoszcz Railway Signal Factory-State Enterprise}}), then in 1958 to ''Bydgoskie Zak\u0142ady Elektromechaniczne'' ({{lang-en|Bydgoszcz Electro-Mechanical Works}}) or ''[[BELMA]]''. In 1951, the factory started to produce for [[Polish People's Army|army]]: it is now its business staple.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belma.pl/historia |title=Historia |last= |first=|date=2020 |website=belma.pl |publisher=Bydgoskie Zak\u0142ady Elektromechaniczne |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\nIn 2018, the firm celebrated its 150th anniversary from its production site located in the vicinity of Bydgoszcz, at [[Bia\u0142e B\u0142ota, Bydgoszcz County|Bia\u0142e B\u0142ota]].\n\nToday are still visible the [[wrought iron]] grate of the main gate, flanked by two front buildings onto Grunwaldzka street at Nos 30 and 32.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 32 34 Belma 1890s.jpg|Picture of the site in the 1890s\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 34'''\n\nEarly 1880s<ref name=\"huit zero\"/>\n\n[[Renaissance Revival architecture|Neo-Renaissance]], elements of [[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo-Baroque]]\n\nThe edifice was initially located on Okole village land, under the adress ''5 Chaussee Stra\u00dfe'': the landlord was Ludwik D\u00fcrr, a butcher. His son Ernst took over the business and ran it till the late 1920s. A butcher shop has been operated there till the outbreak of [[WWII]].<ref name=\"trois trois\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1933 |title=Ksi\u0105\u017cka Adresowa Miasta Bydgoszczy : na rok 1933 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=W\u0142adys\u0142aw Weber|chapter=|pages=29}}</ref>\n\nThe elevation is rendered unbalanced by the heavy [[bossage]]d [[bay window]] featuring a [[loggia]]. The left side shows adorned windows with [[festoon]]s in cartouches, [[pilaster]]s, curved [[pediment]]s bearing a stylized [[coat of arms]] and a top [[corbel]] table.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 34.jpg|Facade at 34 Grunwaldzka\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 7 07-2013.jpg|Detail of the pediment\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 35'''\n\n1850-1900<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nSituated in Schleusenau suburb, at ''9 Lindenstra\u00dfe'', it was the property of a carpenter, Heinrich G\u00fcrich.<ref name=\"neuf zero\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1890 |title=Adressbuch nebst allgemeinem Gesch\u00e4fts-Anzeiger von Bromberg und dessen Vororten auf das Jahr 1890: auf Grund amtlicher und privater Unterlagen |location=Bromberg |publisher=Dittmann|chapter=names |pages=66,82,159}}</ref> In the 1910s, the ground floor housed a plumber store ran by Friedrich Kolbe (see gallery) at ''107 Chaussee stra\u00dfe''.\n\nThe balanced facade has been renovated in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bydgoszczwbudowie.blogspot.com/2017/09/remonty-kamienic-wrzesien-2017.html |title=Remonty kamienic Wrzesie\u0144 2017 |last=|first=|date=September 2017 |website=bydgoszczwbudowie.blogspot.com |publisher=bydgoszczwbudowie |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 35 1910 1914.jpg|F. Kolbe shop in the 1910s\nFile:Grunwaldzka 35.jpg|Renovated elevation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Pharmacy ''Under the lion'' at No. 37'''\n\n1894<ref name=\"okole\"/>, by [[J\u00f3zef \u015awi\u0119cicki]] and [[Bydgoszcz_Architects_(1850-1970s)#Karl_Bergner|Karl Bergner]]\n\n[[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo Baroque]], [[Rococo]] and [[Mannerism#Mannerist_architecture|Mannerism]]\n\nDr Leonhard Tonn began to run a pharmacy at this spot before commissionning the house. He contracted architect J\u00f3zef Swiecicki who worked with Karl Bergner; builder was well-known entrepreneur [[Bydgoszcz_Architects_(1850-1970s)#Carl_Rose|Carl Rose]].<ref name=\"okole\"/> In March 1894 Dr. Tonn established the ''L\u00f6wen Apotheke Laboratorium f\u00fcr chemische und mikroskopische Untersuchungen - Dr. L. Tonn'' ({{lang-en|Under the lion-Pharmacy laboratory for chemical and microscopic analysis}}). On October 15, 1924, while Bydgoszcz ahd reintegrated [[History of Poland (1918\u20131939)|Polish territory]], the shop was sold to Piotr and Henryk Umbreit, two brothers from [[Pozna\u0144]]. In 1880, they had already founded in their city a pharmaceutical and chemical warehouse, at that time the second Polish medicine factory in Pozna\u0144.<ref name=\"ZJ\">{{cite web |url=https://pomorska.pl/wielkopolscy-farmaceuci-zostawili-slad-w-bydgoszczy/ar/6983411 |title=Wielkopolscy farmaceuci zostawili \u015blad w Bydgoszczy|last=Zielazna |first=Jolanta |date=30 July 2008 |website=pomorska.pl |publisher=Gazeta pomorska |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> In parallel, a medical cabinet opened in the house: in May 1926, dr. Teofil Kowalski from Warsaw succeded to dr. Keslinger, from [[Gda\u0144sk]].\nDuring the Second World War, the management of the pharmacy was taken over by German chemist Georg Kubisch, a member of [[Sturmabteilung|SA]] from Gda\u0144sk, and the name changed to ''L\u00f6wen Apotheke''. In 1940, the pharmacy receives the name ''Hindenburg Apotheke'' since it was also used as a training facility for chemistry students. In 1951, the firm was nationalized as ''Social Pharmacy No. 12'', but its original name ''Pod Lwem'' was reinstated in 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last=Czajkowski|first=Edmund |date=1984|title=Apteka \"Pod Lwem\". Kalendarz Bydgoski  |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy | pages=95-97}}</ref>\n\nAt its opening, the pharmacy was equipped with oak furniture imported from [[Berlin]], the bronze lion painted in gold came from Italy.The emblem is one of the few original preserved pharmacy emblems in Poland.<ref name=\"okole\"/> The building boasts a rich decoration dominated by various styles elements ([[Baroque Revival architecture|Neo Baroque]], [[Rococo]] and [[Mannerism#Mannerist_architecture|Mannerism]]). Together with the standing golden lion, the house is characterized by its [[onion dome]] bearing a [[weather vane]] with a lion [[silhouette]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 22 07-2013.jpg|Elevation on the street\nFile:Lion apteka.jpg|Pharmacy emblem\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 37 Bydg 2008 he\u0142m.jpg|Neo Baroque onion dome\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 20 07-2013.jpg|Detail of the weather vane\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 42, corner with Jasna Street'''\n\nEnd of 19th century-1905<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>, by F. Pretzel<ref name=\"okole\"/>\n\n[[Art Nouveau]]\n\nBuilt in Okole suburb at ''7 Chausseestra\u00dfe'', its owner was a merchant, Carl Raddatz.<ref name=\"neuf zero\"/> The Raddatz family kept the property till the outbreak of [[WWII]].<ref name=\"trois trois\"/>\n\nThe building has undergone an overhaul in 2017, underlining the [[stucco]]ed motifs, especially on the [[pediment]]ed wall [[dormer]] giving onto Grunwaldzka street.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 40 42 1908.jpg|The tenement4 in 1908\nFile:Grunwaldzka 42.jpg|View from the street crossing\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 49'''\n\n1885<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nConstructed on Schleusenau ground in the late 1880s, it has been commissionned by Ludwig Wegener, a boatsman.<ref name=\"huit cinq\">{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1885 |title=Wohnungs-Anzeiger nebst Adress- und Gesch\u00e4fts-Handbuch f\u00fcr Bromberg und Umgebung : auf das Jahr 1885 |location=Bromberg |publisher=Mittlersche Buchhandlung (A. Fromm Nachf.)|chapter=|pages=149}}</ref>\n\nThe building endured a renovation in 2016.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 49.jpg|Facade on Grunwaldzka street\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Building at No. 50'''\n\n1958-1959<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Modern architecture]], [[Neoclassical architecture]]\n\nThis large edifice was commissionned by the firm ''[[BELMA]]'' settled at No. 30/32. It was designed as a cultural and educational center ({{lang-pl|Dom Kultury}}) for the benefit of ''BELMA'' employees and later also for students from nearby schools. During holidays in particular, the institution used to organize puppet theater performances and film screenings.<ref name=\"okole\"/> \nToday the edifice houses the [[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship|Kuyavian-Pomeranian]] Tax Office in Bydgoszcz.\n\nThe facility has a large auditorium with a stage. It is an architectural example of [[Stalinist_architecture#Poland|Socialist realist construction]].\nIn Bydgoszcz, it is the second largest public facility built after 1950, after the [[Pomeranian Philharmonic]].\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg ulGrunwaldzka 14 07-2013.jpg|View of the facade on Grunwaldzka street\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka K-PUS Bydg 2008a.jpg|Detail of the [[portal (architecture)|portal]] with [[column]]s\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 53'''{{break}}\nRegistered on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (A/1681 July, 24, 2015).<ref name=\"class\"/>\n\n1890<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nEduard Schulz, the house investor, was a secretary of the railway. The property remained in the hands of the Schulz family during the interwar period.<ref name=\"okole\"/> \n\nOn the facade boasts a collection of ornamentation:\n* a main entrance flanked by [[Corinthian order|corinthian]] style columns;\n* a [[bossage]] wall on the ground floor;\n* the first [[belt course]] supports [[pilaster]]s and a [[column]]ed [[loggia]] with a round [[architrave]];\n* the second string course carries two series of round top [[mullion]]ed windows separated by an [[oeil-de-boeuf]];\n* a large [[cornice]] tops the frontage. \nThis house has been refurbished in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bydgoszcz.pl/aktualnosci/tresc/dbamy-o-zabytki-elewacja-na-okolu-w-pelnej-krasi/ |title=Dbamy o zabytki. Elewacja na Okolu w pe\u0142nej krasie |last=|first=|date=8 January 2020 |website=bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=Miasto Bydgoszcz |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 53 1907.jpg|53 Grunwaldzka on a postcard ca 1907\nFile:Bdg Grunwaldzka53 2 02-2014.jpg|Building before renovation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Building at No. 55'''\n\n1890<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Art Nouveau]]\n\nThe commissionner of this building was Marie Jacobowski, owner of tenements at No. 57 and 59, where she lived.<ref name=\"neuf zero\"/> After a heavy fire damage in 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz998.wordpress.com/2012/12/28/grozny-pozar-mieszkania-przy-ulicy-grunwaldzkiej-55-w-bydgoszczy/ |title=Gro\u017any po\u017car mieszkania przy ulicy Grunwaldzkiej 55 w Bydgoszczy |last=\u017bywoci\u0144ski |first=Artur |date=28 December 2012 |website=bydgoszcz 998 |publisher=bydgoszcz998.wordpress |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> the municpal authorities have decided in 2019 to sell the property to private hands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.naszemiasto.pl/zamiast-pustych-slow-maja-byc-puste-lokale-radny-zrobil/ar/c1-7335829 |title=Zamiast pustych s\u0142\u00f3w maj\u0105 by\u0107 puste lokale. Radny zrobi\u0142 list\u0119 |last=Stasiewicz |first=Anna |date=13 September 2019 |website=bydgoszcz.naszemiasto.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.naszemiasto |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough damaged, the main elevation offers to the viewer topping [[loggia]]s crowned by a [[festoon]], a [[bay window]] with geometrical motifs and an adorned [[portal (architecture)|portal]]. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 53-55 Bydg 2008.jpg|View of elevations at 53 and 55\nFile:Grunwaldzka 55.jpg|Frontage onto the street\nFile:Grunwaldzka 55 portal.jpg|Detail of the portal at 55 Grunwaldzka\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 57/59, corner with Kana\u0142owa street'''\n\nEnd 19th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nBoth buildings (along with No. 55) were the property of Marie Jacobowski, who lived at 59.<ref name=\"neuf zero\"/> Between the early 1900s and the end of the [[Second Polish Republic|interwar]] period, the ground floor at 57 housed a tobacco shop.<ref name=\"trois trois\"/>\n\nFacades did not keep the architectural richness: still noticeable are the corner [[wrought iron]] [[balcony|balconies]] facing each other across Kana\u0142owa street. The tenement at 57 has been refurbished in 2017-2018. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 57 59 1914.jpg|No. 57 59 on a 1914 postcard\nFile:Ul Grunwaldzka 53-57 Bydg 2008b.jpg|Building at 57 (far right) before renovation\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 72/74 and 78'''\n\nEnd 19th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Eclecticism in architecture|Eclecticism]]\n\nWhile No. 72 and 74 had private owners, the tenement at 78 was initially the property of the [[Prussian Eastern Railway]], as its location commanded a view on the line from [[Bydgoszcz|Bromberg]] to [[Kaliningrad]]. After 1920 and the [[History_of_Poland#Second_Polish_Republic_(1918\u20131939)|restoration of the Polish state]], the house was taken over by the ''Bydgoszcz Railway'' ({{lang-pl|Bydgoskie Koleje Powiatowe}}), the local disctrict of the [[Polish State Railways]] ({{lang-pl| Polskie Koleje Pa\u0144stwowe}}).<ref name=\"trois trois\"/> \n\nAll three houses are in a neglected state and few details still prevail, apart from the decoration around the windows ([[pediment]]s, garnished [[lintel]] and cartouches). \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 72 74.jpg|Buildings at 72 74 \nFile:Grunwaldzka 78.jpg|Building at 78 \n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenement at No. 98'''\n\nEarly 20th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Art Nouveau]]\n\nThe commissionner was Heinrich Seellen.<ref name=\"zero un\"/>\n\nThe building has been deeply refurbished in 2019, after a sell by the municipal authorities to a private company.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bydgoszcz.pl/aktualnosci/tresc/odnowiona-kamienica-zdobi-ulice-grunwaldzka/ |title=Odnowiona kamienica zdobi ulic\u0119 Grunwaldzk\u0105 |last=|first=|date=15 January 2019 |website=bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=Miasto Bydgoszcz |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The thorough renovation highlights\n[[Art Nouveau]] motifs, such as the [[stucco]]ed patterns on the top of each wall [[gable]] crowing the two [[terrace]]s. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Grunwaldzka 98.jpg|98 Grunwaldzka before restoration\nFile:Grunwaldzka 98 2.jpg|98 Grunwaldzka refurbished\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Tenements at No. 102 to 118'''\n\nEarly 20th century<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Modern_architecture]]\n\nThe ensemble was owned by the [[Prussian Eastern Railway]] ({{lang-de|Preu\u00dfische Ostbahn}}) and built in three stages: 1904 (houses 108 to 114), then 1911 (102 and 104) and 1912 (116-118). The railway company housed here its employees, mostly drivers and auxiliary staff, together with some low-level officials. Up to 50 families used to be accommodated in this housing blocks.<ref name=\"okole\"/>\n\nA modern project of residence is planned to be squeezed at 106 (only free plot) in 2020.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg ul Grunwaldzka 4 5-2015.jpg|Housing ensemble along the street\nFile:Bdg ul Grunwaldzka 2 5-2015.jpg|One of the houses\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Catholic church Saint [[Anthony of Padua]], crossing with Koronowska street'''\n\nRegistered on the '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (No.690851 A/1159 August 3, 2006).<ref name=\"class\"/>\n\n1936-1945<ref name=\"ZAR\"/>\n\n[[Modern architecture]]\n\nAt the time of the re-creation of the Polish state, the area was part of the ''Czy\u017ck\u00f3wko'' village, which will be combined with Bydgoszcz territory in the late 1920s. The new district was subordinated to the downtown [[Church of the Holy Trinity in Bydgoszcz|parish of the Holy Trinity]], several kilometers away. In this situation, a dance hall was purchased in 1923 to be replaced by a chapel, [[consecration|consecrated]] on February 24, 1924.<ref name=\"padova\">{{cite book |last=Wysocka |first=Agnieszka|date=2008 |title=Ko\u015bcio\u0142y projektu Stefana Cybichowskiego w Bydgoszczy i okolicach miasta. Kronika Bydgoska XXX |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy| pages= |language=pl}}</ref>\n\nA request to create a new parish in this area was granted by [[Primate (bishop)|bishop]] [[August Hlond]] and the parish was inaugurated on July 1, 1933, dedicated to [[Anthony of Padua]], hence endorsing the separation from the Holy Trinity church. The construction of the church, funded partly by [[Antoni Laubitz]], the bishop of [[Gniezno]], began in 1936: the design was realized a year earlier by [[Pozna\u0144]] architect Stefan Cybichowski.<ref name=\"padova\"/> The edifice was not completed at the start of [[WWII]] and had been used by Nazi forces as a warehouse for construction tools, while religious services were held back in the initial chapel.\nAfter the war, the church was left devastated and shelled, but after a hasty renovation, it had been consecrated anew by bishop [[August Hlond]] on December 1, 1945.<ref name=\"padova\"/>\n\nThe massive brick church has three [[nave]]s, with a semi-circular northern [[chancel]]. The highlight of the building is the high square [[steeple]], visible from Grunwaldzka street crossing. Inside, several [[stained glass]]es cover the openings. \nThe central nave is separated by [[pillar]]s with decorative goblets [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]] supporting a [[Barrel vault|vaulted roof]].<ref name=\"padova\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:38. kosciol padewskiego bydgoszcz.JPG|View from the church parvis\nFile:Bydgoszcz Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw Antoniego 2.jpg|External view of the chancel\nFile:Bydgoszcz Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw Antoniego 1.jpg|Detail of the steeple, still bearing some 1945 damages\nFile:Kosciol sw Antoniego Padewskiego Consecration 1945.jpg|Leaflet for the 1945 consecration\n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Catholic church Saint [[Maximilian Kolbe]], corner with Kolibrowa street'''\n\n1982-1991\n\n[[Modern architecture]]\n\nGrunwaldzka street cuts through a patch of forest before entering another urban area where stands the church.\nA pastoral center has been active in this area since in 1970. One of its member, Jadwiga Wo\u015b, donated a swathe of her land to have a chapel built. A first service was celebrated there on March 9, 1972, for the ten following years. The parish ''St. Maximilian Kolbe'' was erected on July 1, 1981.<ref name=\"hist paraf\">{{cite web |url=http://mkolbe.bydgoszcz.pl/o-parafii/historia-parafii/ |title=Historia parafii |last=|first=|date=2017 |website=mkolbe.bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=Parafia pw. \u015bw. Maksymiliana Kolbego |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> \nThe cornerstone of the church (coming from an ancient roman temple on Lech Hill in Gniezno) was laid on May 25, 1983 in a ceremony attended among others by the Primate of Poland, [[J\u00f3zef Glemp]]. On May 26, 1991, Cardinal J\u00f3zef Glemp solemnly consecrated the new church in the [[Osowa G\u00f3ra (Bydgoszcz district)|Osowa G\u00f3ra district]].\n\nThe church is built in a modern style. On the main wall of the chancel one can admire a 7-m-high bronze [[bas-relief]] of the Parish [[Patron saint]]. The architectural structure also comprises [[catechesis|catechetical]] rooms, a parish office and a daily chapel.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bird eye forest.jpg|Grunwaldzka street through the forest before reaching the church\nFile:Bydgoszcz Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw Maksymiliana Kolbe 2.jpg|View of the church from the street \nFile:Osowa G\u00f3ra Parafia rzymskokatolicka pw.\u015bw Maksymiliana Kolbego - panoramio.jpg|Northern view\nFile:OsowaGora ParafiaA 2.JPG|The chancel with the bas-relief \n</gallery>\n{{break|2}}\n'''Restaurant ''Karczma Rzym'' '''\n\nThe last estate on Grunwaldzka street prior to leaving Bydgoszcz territory, is  ''Karczma Rzym'' ({{lang-en|[[Rome]] Inn}}), a traditional restaurant.\nIt offers traditional Polish cuisine and bears a name widely spread in Poland for such an establishment .\n\n''Karczma Rzym'' alludes to [[Adam Mickiewicz]]'s [[Pan Twardowski]], where a sorcerer (Twardowski) sellshis soul to the devil in exchange for eternal life and special powers. However, Twardowski, willing to ouwit the devil, includes a special clause in the contract, stating that Satan will own Twardowski's soul only if he visits Rome \u2013 a place the sorcerer never intends to go to. The devil's trick relied on luring the sorcerer into a newly built tavern called ''Rome Inn''.\n\nLegend has it that Pan Twardowski spent some time in [[Bydgoszcz]], where, as a celebration as well as a touristic attraction, a figure was recently mounted in a window of a tenement, overseeing the [[Old Market square, Bydgoszcz|Old Market square]]. Every day at 13:13 and 21:13, third storey window at No.15 opens and Pan Twardowski appears, accompanied by music and a devilish laughter. He takes a bow, waves his hand, and then disappears, to the delight of gathered spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://visitbydgoszcz.pl/en/explore/what-to-see/2568-master-twardowski |title=MASTER TWARDOWSKI |last=|first=|date=2018 |website=visitbydgoszcz.pl |publisher=visitbydgoszcz |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Karczma Rzym.jpg|Restaurant Karczma Rzym\nFile:Pan Twardowski 09 2009.jpg|Pan Twardowski statue in Bydgoszcz\nFile:Stary Rynek Bydg Twardowski.jpg|No.15 on Old Market Place\n</gallery>\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Grunwaldzka Street in Bydgoszcz}}\n* [[Bydgoszcz]]\n* [[Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street in Bydgoszcz|Swi\u0119tej Trojcy street]]\n* [[BELMA]]\n* [[Pan Twardowski]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Br\u0119czewska-Kulesza|first=Daria|date=2004 |title=Przegl\u0105d styl\u00f3w wyst\u0119puj\u0105cych w bydgoskiej architekturze drugiej po\u0142owy XIX i pocz\u0105tku XX stulecia. Bydgoszcz w stron\u0119 Okola |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Zesp\u00f3\u0142 Pracowni Dokumentacji i Popularyzacji Zabytk\u00f3w Wojew\u00f3dzkiego O\u015brodka Kultury w Bydgoszczy| pages=| ISBN=83-921725-0-7|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=Czachorowski |first=Antoni |date=1997 |title=Atlas historyczny miast polskich. Tom II Kujawy. Zeszyt I Bydgoszcz. |location=Toru\u0144 |publisher=Uniwersytet Miko\u0142aja Kopernika| pages=| ISBN=|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=Derenda |first=Jerzy |date=2006 |title=Pi\u0119kna stara Bydgoszcz. Tom I z serii: Bydgoszcz miasto na Kujawach |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy| pages=| ISBN=83-916178-0-7|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jastrz\u0119bska-Puzowska|first=Iwona|date=2005 |title=Od miasteczka do metropolii. Rozw\u00f3j architektoniczny i urbanistyczny Bydgoszczy w latach 1850-1920 |location=Toru\u0144 |publisher=Wydawnictwo MADO| pages=| ISBN=83-89886-38-3|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last= |first= |author-link= |date=2004 |title=Bydgoszcz w stron\u0119 Okola. |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Zesp\u00f3\u0142 Pracowni Dokumentacji i Popularyzacji Zabytk\u00f3w Wojew\u00f3dzkiego O\u015brodka Kultury w Bydgoszczy |page= |isbn=83-921725-0-7|language=pl}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cmentarze.bydgoszcz.pl/ ''Starofarny'' Municipal cemetery]\n* [http://www.belma.pl/en/ BELMA company]\n* [https://www.kujawsko-pomorskie.kas.gov.pl/kujawsko-pomorski-urzad-skarbowy-w-bydgoszczy/kontakt/dane-teleadresowe Kuyavian-Pomeranian Tax Office in Bydgoszcz]\n* [https://antonibydgoszcz.pl/ Saint Anthony Parish] \n* [http://mkolbe.bydgoszcz.pl/ Saint Maximilian Kolbe Parish]\n* [https://www.karczmarzym.com.pl/ Restaurant Karczma Rzym]\n\n\n{{coord|53|08|29|N|17|56|29|E|source:wikimapia|display=title}}\n{{Bydgoszcz streets and squares}}\n \n[[:Category:Cultural heritage monuments in Bydgoszcz]]\n[[:Category:Streets and squares in Bydgoszcz]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:street car\u2192Streetcar,terrace\u2192terraced house", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grunwaldzka_street_in_Bydgoszcz"}
